{"title_page": "Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019", "text_new": "{{short description|Act of the Parliament of India}}\n\n{{Distinguish|Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox legislation\n| short_title = The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019\n| legislature =\n| image =\n| imagesize = 100\n| imagealt = Emblem of India\n| long_title = An Act to provide for protection of rights of transgender persons and their welfare and for matters connected therewith and incidental thereto.\n| citation =\n| territorial_extent = [[Republic of India]]\n| enacted_by = [[Parliament of India]]\n| date_passed = 5 August 2019\n| date_passed2 = 26 November 2019\n| date_assented = 5 December 2019\n| date_signed = 5 December 2019\n| date_commenced = 10 January 2020\n| bill =\n\n| bill_citation = Bill No. 169 of 2019\n| act_citation = Act No. 40 of 2019\n[http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/The%20Transgender%20Persons%20%28Protection%20of%20Rights%29%20Bill%2C%202019%20Bill%20Text.pdf]\n| bill_date = 19 July 2019\n| introduced_by = Minister for Social Justice and Empowerment\n| 1st_reading = 5 August 2019\n| 2nd_reading =\n| 3rd_reading =\n| white_paper =\n| committee_report = [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/SCR-%20Transgender%20Bill.pdf   43rd Report by Standing Committee on Social Justice and Empowerment, July 2017]\n| amendments =\n| repeals =\n| related = [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Transgender%20persons%20bill%20as%20passed%20by%20LS.pdf        The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2018]<br/>[http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Transgender_Persons_Bill%2C_2016_1.pdf  The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2016]<br/>[[Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014|The Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014]]\n| summary =\n| keywords =\n| status = In force\n\n}}\n\nThe '''Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019''' is an [[Act (law)|act]] of the [[Parliament of India]] with the objective to provide for protection of rights of [[Transgender|transgender persons]], their welfare, and other related matters. The act was introduced in the [[Lok Sabha]], the lower house of the Parliament, on 19 July 2019 by the [[Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment|Minister of Social Justice and Empowerment]], [[Thawar Chand Gehlot]], in light of the lapse of the Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2018. The 2019 act and the immediately preceding 2018 bill, were both preceded by a 2016 version,. They were met with protests and criticism by transgender persons, lawyers, and activists in India. The 2016 bill was sent to a [[Standing committee (India)|standing committee]] which submitted its report in July  2017. Following this, the Lok Sabha tabled and passed a newer version of the bill in December 2018. However, it did not incorporate many of the committee's recommendations. Although members of the opposition criticised the 2019 act and assured transgender persons of not voting in favour of it, it was passed by the Lok Sabha on 5 August 2019 and by the [[Rajya Sabha]], the upper house of the Parliament, on 26 November 2019. The [[President of India|president]] assented to it on 5 December 2019, upon which the act was notified in the ''[[Gazette of India]]''. It was brought into effect from 10 January 2020 onwards vide a notification in the ''Gazette'' on the same day.\n\nFollowing protests by the [[LGBT|queer community]] against the 2016 and 2018 bills, the 2019 act has done away with few of the severely criticised provisions of the 2018 bill, such as criminalisation of begging and the establishment of a district screening committee to process applications for issuance of transgender person certificates. However, it fails to incorporate yet other principles in line with the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] judgment in ''[[National Legal Services Authority v. Union of India]]'' (''NALSA v. UOI'') in 2014, such as the right of transgender persons to self-perceived gender identity without undergoing [[sex reassignment surgery]], and mandatory reservations in jobs and educational institutions. The act has also been criticised for the lesser punishment for crimes against transgender persons compared with punishment for crimes against [[cisgender|cisgender persons]]. On 27 January 2020, the Supreme Court issued a notice to the central government in a petition filed challenging the constitutionality of the 2019 legislation\n\nIn January 2014, while judicial pronouncement in the ''NALSA'' petition was pending, the ministry had published an Expert Committee Report on issues relating to transgender persons, after consultations with transgender persons. [[Tiruchi Siva]], of the [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]] party, had introduced the [[Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014|Rights of Transgender Persons Bill]] in 2014, in the Rajya Sabha, which was passed by the house in 2015. The 2014 bill contains provisions progressive to those in the bills introduced in between 2016 and 2019, but has been pending in the Lok Sabha since 2015. Prior to the [[Indian general elections, 2019|2019 general elections]], parties such as the [[Indian National Congress]] and [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] had promised in their respective electoral manifestoes to, respectively, withdraw the 2018 bill \u2014 while introducing a new one consulting members of the queer community \u2014 and pass the 2014 bill.\n\n==History and background==\n[[File:Hijra and companions in Eastern Bengal.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Hijras in eastern Bengal, ''circa'' 1860]]\n{{LGBT rights}}\nIn 2014, the Supreme Court of India delivered its judgment in ''National Legal Services Authority v. Union of India'' (also known as, ''NALSA v. UOI''), in which it recognised the rights of the transgender persons in India and laid down a series of measures for securing transgender persons' rights by mandating prohibition of discrimination, recommending the creation of welfare policies and reservations for transgender persons in educational institutions and jobs.<ref name=\"th1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/supreme-court-recognises-transgenders-as-third-gender/article5914572.ece | title=Supreme Court recognises transgenders as third gender | date=15 April 2014 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Venkatesan, J. | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614152049/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/supreme-court-recognises-transgenders-as-third-gender/article5914572.ece | archive-date=14 June 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> The judgment upheld the right of a transgender person to self-perceived gender identity, guaranteed by the [[Constitution of India]], in the absence of sex reassignment surgery.<ref name=\"th2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/a-promise-falls-short/article23505892.ece | title=A promise falls short | date=12 April 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kothari, Jayna}}</ref> The 2014 judicial mandate stands backed by the judgments of the Supreme Court in ''[[Justice K. S. Puttaswamy (Retd.) and Anr. vs Union Of India And Ors.|Justice K. S. Puttaswamy (Retd.) and anr. v. Union of India and ors.]]'' (2017) and ''[[Navtej Singh Johar v. Union of India]]'' (2018).<ref name=\"th3\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/the-supreme-court-trans-formed/article24949441.ece | title=The Supreme Court trans-formed | date=15 September 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kothari, Jayna}}</ref> The judgment in ''NALSA v. UOI'' also noted the presence of transgender persons in India throughout its history, and made reference to the [[Hijra (South Asia)|hijra, kinnar, and jogta]] communities, spread across the country and beyond in the [[Indian subcontinent]].<ref>{{cite journal | title=National Legal Services Authority versus Union of India and others | journal=Supreme Court Cases | year=2014 | volume=5 | pages=438}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-27031180 | title=India court recognises transgender people as third gender | date=15 April 2014 | agency=BBC | accessdate=17 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811110426/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-27031180 | archive-date=11 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile the decision in the ''NALSA'' petition was still pending, an expert committee report on issues relating to transgender persons was published in January 2014, after consultations by the Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment with transgender persons in August 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/rights-wrongs/article21339721.ece | title=Rights & wrongs \u2014 on Transgender Persons Bill | date=9 December 2017 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625123619/http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/rights-wrongs/article21339721.ece | archive-date=25 June 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/expert-panel-wants-transgender-declared-third-gender/article5781874.ece | title=Expert panel wants transgender declared third gender | date=24 March 2014 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Dhar, Aarti | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224013224/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/expert-panel-wants-transgender-declared-third-gender/article5781874.ece | archive-date=24 December 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> In this background, Tiruchi Siva of the Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam party introduced a [[private member's bill]] in the Rajya Sabha, namely the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill (No.  XLIXC-C), 2014.<ref name =\"transpvt\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/rajya-sabha-passes-private-bill-on-transgenders/article7138056.ece | title=RS passes Bill on transgender rights | date=24 April 2015 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Gandhi and, Ramachandran | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510072419/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/rajya-sabha-passes-private-bill-on-transgenders/article7138056.ece | archive-date=10 May 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe government had initially asked him to withdraw the bill citing various anomalies; however, the opposition had a majority in the house and the bill was unanimously passed by the Rajya Sabha on 24 April 2015.<ref name=\"transpvt\" /> The bill was welcomed by queer rights activists in India.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/turning-point-in-transgender-rights/article7139875.ece | title=\"Turning point in transgender rights\" | date=25 April 2015 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Srinivasan, Meera | location=Chennai}}</ref> However, some transgender persons noted their absence in the entire process and called for their recommendations being sought for.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/activists-oppose-bill-on-transgender-rights/article7993938.ece | title=Activists oppose Bill on transgender rights | date=16 December 2015 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=Bengaluru}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/cant-erase-hijra-culture-transgender-persons-bill-1581247-2019-08-16 | title=\"We can't erase our hijra culture\" | date=16 August 2019 | agency=India Today | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Sinha, Chinki | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816153625/https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/cant-erase-hijra-culture-transgender-persons-bill-1581247-2019-08-16 | archive-date=16 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Following the passing of the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014 in 2015, it stood to be the first private member's bill to be passed by the Rajya Sabha in the preceding thirty-six years<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Rajya-Sabha-passes-first-private-members-bill-in-36-years-on-transgenders-rights/articleshow/47039967.cms | title=Rajya Sabha passes first private member's bill in 36 years, on transgenders' rights | date=25 April 2015 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831081935/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Rajya-Sabha-passes-first-private-members-bill-in-36-years-on-transgenders-rights/articleshow/47039967.cms | archive-date=31 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> and by the Parliament in the preceding forty-five years.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rajya-sabha-private-member-bill-transgenders-rights-250096-2015-04-24 | title=Rajya Sabha passes transgenders rights bill, first private member proposal in 46 years | date=24 April 2015 | agency=India Today | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817114840/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rajya-sabha-private-member-bill-transgenders-rights-250096-2015-04-24 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Until 2015, only sixteen private member's bills had stood passed since 1947.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Just-14-private-members-bills-passed-by-Parliament-till-date-the-last-was-in-1970/articleshow/47046338.cms | title=Just 14 private member's bill passed by Parliament till date; the last was in 1970 | date=25 April 2015 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907004217/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Just-14-private-members-bills-passed-by-Parliament-till-date-the-last-was-in-1970/articleshow/47046338.cms | archive-date=7 September 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe 2014 bill underwent significant changes when the government drafted its own version of the bill, with omissions of provisions in the 2014 bill.<ref name = \"2015bill\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/all-you-need-to-know-about-the-transgender-persons-bill-2016/article21226710.ece | title=All you need to know about the Transgender Persons Bill, 2016 | date=30 November 2017 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Abraham, Rohan | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507193832/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/all-you-need-to-know-about-the-transgender-persons-bill-2016/article21226710.ece | archive-date=7 May 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> After recommendations were received from transgender persons, the bill was sent to the [[Ministry of Law and Justice (India)|Ministry of Law and Justice]].<ref name = \"2015bill\"/> It came to be known as the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2015.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bill-ensures-family-life-for-transgender-children/articleshow/50374808.cms | title=Bill ensures family life for transgender children | date=30 December 2015 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=19 August 2019 | author=Ghildiyal, Subodh | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901033429/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bill-ensures-family-life-for-transgender-children/articleshow/50374808.cms | archive-date=1 September 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Later, on 26 February 2016, the bill was introduced in the Lok Sabha for debate by [[Baijayant Panda]] of the [[Biju Janata Dal]] party.<ref name=\"bjd\">{{cite news | url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/lok-sabha-takes-up-bill-to-end-transgender-discrimination-1281768 | title=Lok Sabha Takes Up Bill To End Transgender Discrimination | date=27 February 2016 | agency=NDTV | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=PTI | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817124856/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/lok-sabha-takes-up-bill-to-end-transgender-discrimination-1281768 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> He argued that the bill would help extend constitutional rights and end the discrimination against transgender people, allowing them to live a life of dignity.<ref name=\"bjd\"/> The bill was discussed in the Lok Sabha on 29 April 2016.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/live-today-in-parliament-april-29-2016/article8536287.ece | title=Lok Sabha discusses transgender rights | date=29 April 2016 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> Siva stated that he will not be withdrawing the 2014 bill.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/article/906587/how-parliament-came-to-have-two-bills-on-transgender-persons-rights-and-why-neither-may-pass | title=How Parliament came to have two Bills on transgender persons\u2019 rights (and why neither may pass) | date=24 December 2018 | agency=Scroll | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Lalwani, Vijayta | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103306/https://scroll.in/article/906587/how-parliament-came-to-have-two-bills-on-transgender-persons-rights-and-why-neither-may-pass | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile the 2014 bill passed by the Rajya Sabha continues to be pending,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/rajya-sabha-member-wants-to-modify-national-anthem/article28100859.ece | title=Rajya Sabha member wants to modify National Anthem | date=21 June 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> the government tabled the Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill (No. 210), 2016, on 2 August 2016, following the constitution of the Lok Sabha, post the [[Indian general elections, 2014|2014 general elections]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/explained-why-the-citizenship-amendment-bill-is-dead-for-now-5582573/ | title=Explained: Why the Citizenship Amendment Bill is dead, for now | date=13 February 2019 | agency=Indian Express | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817130024/https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/explained-why-the-citizenship-amendment-bill-is-dead-for-now-5582573/ | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The 2016 bill had various provisions regressive to the provisions in the 2014 bill.<ref name=\"scroll\">{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/article/906205/this-is-a-black-day-activists-criticise-transgender-persons-bill-passed-in-lok-sabha | title=\u2018This is a black day\u2019: Activists criticise Transgender Persons Bill passed in Lok Sabha | date=19 December 2018 | agency=Scroll | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Lalwani, Vijayta | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103231/https://scroll.in/article/906205/this-is-a-black-day-activists-criticise-transgender-persons-bill-passed-in-lok-sabha | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"jyotiratnam\" /> The bill was met with criticism and protests from Indian transgender persons and was referred to the standing committee, which submitted its report in July 2018.<ref name=\"jyotiratnam\" /> The Lok Sabha tabled and passed a newer version of the bill with twenty-seven amendments on 17 December 2018.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://ptinews.com/news/10250267_Lok-Sabha-passes-Transgender-bill.html | title=Lok Sabha passes Transgender bill | date=17 December 2018 | agency=PRI | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817092137/http://ptinews.com/news/10250267_Lok-Sabha-passes-Transgender-bill.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"bittuh1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-transgender-persons-bill-misses-key-demands-of-the-community/story-0c6VV1GvYuV4xqYL06zw8N.html | title=The Transgender Persons Bill misses key demands of the community | date=15 June 2019 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kondaiah, Karthik Bittu | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817053704/https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-transgender-persons-bill-misses-key-demands-of-the-community/story-0c6VV1GvYuV4xqYL06zw8N.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The bill was once again met with severe criticism and protests pan-India, as it overlooked the recommendations made by the standing committee and suggestions offered by transgender persons.<ref name=\"revised\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/colleges-join-hands-to-protest-against-transgender-bill-2018/article25844976.ece | title=Colleges join hands to protest against Transgender Bill 2018 | date=28 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Karangutkar, Suyash | location=Mumbai}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/rights-revised/article25783926.ece | title=Rights, revised: on the Transgender Persons Bill, 2018 | date=20 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> However, the 2018 bill stood lapsed.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-rights-bill-to-be-reintroduced/article27474400.ece | title=Transgender rights Bill to be reintroduced | date=5 June 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the constitution of the Lok Sabha, post the 2019 general elections, the bill was reintroduced on 19 July 2019 by the Minister of Social Justice and Empowerment, [[Thawar Chand Gehlot]].<ref name=\"leaflet1\">{{cite news | url=https://theleaflet.in/transgender-bill-introduced-in-the-lok-sabha/ | title=Transgender Bill introduced in the Lok Sabha | date=24 July 2019 | agency=The Leaflet | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Sirohi, Nishant | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817092851/https://theleaflet.in/transgender-bill-introduced-in-the-lok-sabha/ | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Before this the bill had been approved by the [[Cabinet of India|union cabinet]] on 10 July 2019.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/cabinet-approves-transgender-bill/article28355950.ece | title=Cabinet approves transgender bill | work=The Hindu Business Line | date=10 July 2019 | agency=Press Trust of India | accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> The bill was passed by a voice vote in the Lok Sabha on 5 August 2019, amidst commotion on the house following the revocation of Jammu and Kashmir's special status by the Parliament on the same day.<ref name=\"passedaugust\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-persons-bill-passed-in-lok-sabha/article28822000.ece | title=Transgender Persons bill passed in Lok Sabha | date=5 August 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=PTI | location=New Delhi}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/congress-opposition-parties-protest-in-lok-sabha-seek-presence-of-prime-minister-on-kashmir-decisions/articleshow/70536012.cms | title=Congress opposition parties protest in Lok Sabha seek presence of Prime Minister on Kashmir decision | date=5 August 2019 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808023548/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/congress-opposition-parties-protest-in-lok-sabha-seek-presence-of-prime-minister-on-kashmir-decisions/articleshow/70536012.cms | archive-date=8 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The bill was introduced in the Rajya Sabha by Thawarchand Gehlot on 20 November 2019, upon which it was passed without any amendments on 26 November 2019 following a motion to refer it to a [[Select_committee#India|select committee]] that failed by 77 noes against 55 ayes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/parliament-passes-bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders/article30087790.ece |title=Parliament passes Bill to protect rights of transgenders |work=26 November 2019 |access-date=17 April 2020 |publisher=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130183741/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/parliament-passes-bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders/article30087790.ece |archive-date=30 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name =\"jaya2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/amid-opposition-trans-community-rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-bill-112971 |title=Amid opposition from trans community, Rajya Sabha passes Transgender Persons Bill |date=26 November 2019 |work=The News Minute |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414175331/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/amid-opposition-trans-community-rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-bill-112971 |archive-date=14 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/rajya-sabha-passes-criticised-transgender-rights-bill |title=Rajya Sabha Passes Controversial Transgender Rights Bill |date=26 November 2019 |work=The Wire |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128190253/https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/rajya-sabha-passes-criticised-transgender-rights-bill |archive-date=28 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The bill received presidential assent on 5 December 2019, following which the Ministry of Law and Justice notified it in the ''Gazette of India'' as Act No. 40 of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://socialjustice.nic.in/writereaddata/UploadFile/TG%20bill%20gazette.pdf |title=The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019 [No. 40 of 2019] |date=5 December 2019 |website=socialjustice.nic.in |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412014303/http://socialjustice.nic.in/writereaddata/UploadFile/TG%20bill%20gazette.pdf |archive-date=12 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name= \"despite\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/despite-massive-protests-trans-bill-gets-president-s-assent-becomes-law-113643 |title=Despite massive protests, Trans Bill gets President\u2019s assent, becomes law |date=7 December 2019 |work=The News Minute |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304050316/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/despite-massive-protests-trans-bill-gets-president-s-assent-becomes-law-113643 |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The act came into effect from 10 January 2020 onwards vide a notification in the ''Gazette'' on the same day by the Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2020/215301.pdf |title=Notification, Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment |date=10 January 2020 |website=egazette.nic.in |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111034026/http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2020/215301.pdf |archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Nath |first=Damini |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-persons-act-comes-into-effect/article30545336.ece |title=Transgender Persons Act comes into effect |date=11 January 2020 |work=The Hindu |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229091631/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-persons-act-comes-into-effect/article30545336.ece |archive-date=29 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Statutory provisions==\nThe 2018 bill had criminalised begging \u2014 which transgender persons in India, such as the hijras and jogtas, engage in as a ritual-custom while some rely on it for livelihood \u2014 apart from mandating applications made to the [[District magistrate (India)|district magistrate]] to be screened through a district screening committee for issuance of transgender person certificates.<ref name =\"indiatoday2017\"/><ref name=\"billreaction1\"/> The screening committee was to be composed of five people including a chief medical officer, district social welfare officer, psychologist/psychiatrist, and a representative of the transgender persons<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.prsindia.org/billtrack/transgender-persons-protection-rights-bill-2016 | title=The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2016 | publisher=PRS Legislative Research | accessdate=19 August 2019 | author=PRS India | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819031027/http://www.prsindia.org/billtrack/transgender-persons-protection-rights-bill-2016 | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/against-the-mandate-for-inclusion/article25791080.ece | title=Against the mandate for inclusion: the Transgender Persons Bill 2018 | date=21 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=19 August 2019 | author=Banerjie, Ajita}}</ref> The 2018 bill had also not provided for mandatory reservations for transgender persons and mandated lower punishment for crimes against transgender persons, as compared to punishment for crimes against cisgender persons under the [[Indian Penal Code]].<ref name =\"jyotiratnam\"/><ref name=\"bittuh1\"/> It also ensured a family-life for transgender children, by prohibiting their separation from their family, without taking into account harassment and discrimination they may face within their family as a result of which they may choose to be separated and reside with transgender persons.<ref name = \"herald\"/><ref name = \"economic\"/> A transgender child, as per the provisions, could be separated from their family only by a court order.<ref name = \"revised\"/> The 2018 bill provided for undergoing sex reassignment surgery as a mandatory pre-requirement to be identified as male or female.<ref name =\"frontline\">{{Cite news |url=https://frontline.thehindu.com/dispatches/article25957990.ece |title=Stiff opposition to transgender persons Bill |last=Venkatesan |first=V. |date=10 January 2019 |work=Frontline |access-date=20 September 2019 |last2=Kaur |first2=Tanveer}}</ref> The 2019 act does away only with few of the criticised provisions of the 2018 bill, such as the district screening committee and the criminalisation of begging.<ref name=\"reuters1\"/>\n\nThe statutory provisions of the 2019 act prohibit discrimination against transgender persons.<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-lgbt-lawmaking/india-introduces-new-trans-rights-bill-in-parliament-after-backlash-idUSKCN1UE28S | title=India introduces new trans rights bill in parliament after backlash | date=19 July 2019 | agency=Reuters | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Banerji, Annie | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817074604/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-lgbt-lawmaking/india-introduces-new-trans-rights-bill-in-parliament-after-backlash-idUSKCN1UE28S | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Similar to the 2018 bill, the 2019 act includes [[intersex|intersex persons]], hijras, jogtas, and [[kinnar]]s within its definition of transgender persons,<ref name =\"frontline\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/govt-making-rules-for-us-without-us-transgenders/article29104679.ece | title=Govt. making rules for us without us: transgenders | date=16 August 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Aggarwal, Aarushi | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815231759/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/govt-making-rules-for-us-without-us-transgenders/article29104679.ece | archive-date=15 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> though it does not define terms such as trans-man, trans-woman, and [[genderqueer]].<ref name =\"frontline\"/><ref name=\"tribune1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/comment/bringing-transgenders-into-mainstream/807918.html |title=Bringing transgenders into mainstream |last=Quraishi |first=S. Y. |date=26 July 2019 |work=The Tribune |accessdate=17 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817104013/https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/comment/bringing-transgenders-into-mainstream/807918.html |archive-date=17 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Both, the 2019 act as well as the 2018 bill, describe a transgender person as someone whose gender does not match with the gender assigned to them at birth.<ref name =\"frontline\"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/The%20Transgender%20Persons%20%28Protection%20of%20Rights%29%20Bill%2C%202019%20Bill%20Text.pdf |title=The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill (No. 169), 2019 |work=PRS Legislative Research |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nUnder the provisions of the 2019 act, a transgender person can apply to the district magistrate for a transgender person certificate which will give them the right to change the name on their birth certificate and have all documents updated accordingly.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/transgender-rights-bill-a-stunted-understanding-of-gender-and-equality | title=Transgender Rights Bill: A Stunted Understanding of Gender and Equality | date=5 August 2019 | agency=The Wire | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Gandhi, and Ghia | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802165656/https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/transgender-rights-bill-a-stunted-understanding-of-gender-and-equality | archive-date=2 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> However, similar to the 2018 bill provisions, a transgender person can be identified as male or female only after applying for a revised certificate to the district magistrate, post sex reassignment surgery.<ref name=\"newsminute1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/why-transgender-persons-bill-2018-public-health-nightmare-community-94206 | title=Why Transgender Persons Bill 2018 is a healthcare nightmare for the community | date=30 December 2018 | agency=The News Minute | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Karpagam, Sylvia | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817074604/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/why-transgender-persons-bill-2018-public-health-nightmare-community-94206 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe 2019 act also protects transgender children and provides for states and institutions to come up with adequate policies for the welfare of transgender persons.<ref name=\"dh\">{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders-passed-in-ls-752193.html | title=Bill to protect rights of transgenders passed in LS | date=5 August 2019 | agency=Deccan Herald | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kumar, Prakash | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817095008/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders-passed-in-ls-752193.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name = \"economic\">{{cite news | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/transgender-rights-bill-introduced-in-lok-sabha-may-be-taken-up-next-week/articleshow/70301454.cms | title=Transgender Rights Bill introduced in Lok Sabha, may be taken up next week | date=20 July 2019 | agency=Economic Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Sharma, Nidhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817094010/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/transgender-rights-bill-introduced-in-lok-sabha-may-be-taken-up-next-week/articleshow/70301454.cms | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Similar to the provisions of the 2018 bill, under the provisions of the 2019 act a transgender child can be separated from their family by a court order.<ref name = \"revised\"/> However, unlike the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014 neither the 2018 nor the 2019 act provide for mandatory reservations for transgender persons in educational institutions and jobs.<ref name=\"leaflet1\"/> The 2014 bill had provided for two per-cent reservations in educational institutions and public employment.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/a-law-that-defeats-its-purpose/article25854190.ece | title=A law that defeats its purpose | date=29 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kothari, Jayna}}</ref> Similar to the 2018 bill, the 2019 act provides for punishment for crimes against transgender persons, which stands as an imprisonment for a term not less than six months but which may extend to two years and a fine.<ref name =\"jyotiratnam\"/><ref name =\"tribune1\"/> The 2019 act, as well as the 2018 bill, also provide for the constitution of a National Council for Transgender Persons.<ref name = \"passedaugust\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-lok-sabha-passes-bill-to-prohibit-discrimination-against-transgenders-2779179 | title=Lok Sabha passes bill to prohibit discrimination against transgenders | date=5 August 2019 | agency=DNA | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=ANI | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806145618/https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-lok-sabha-passes-bill-to-prohibit-discrimination-against-transgenders-2779179 | archive-date=6 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism and reactions==\n[[File:Protest against Transgender Bill in Mumbai, India.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Protests against the 2018 bill in [[Mumbai]], in December 2018]]\nThe 2018 bill passed by the Lok Sabha was widely criticised by transgender persons, activists, students, and lawyers.<ref name=\"gautamh1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-rajya-sabha-must-amend-the-transgender-persons-bill/story-WEyPFztPVABpfaQyDYBt5I.html | title=The Rajya Sabha must amend the Transgender Persons Bill | date=5 January 2019 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Bhatia, Gautam | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817073521/https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-rajya-sabha-must-amend-the-transgender-persons-bill/story-WEyPFztPVABpfaQyDYBt5I.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Transgender persons protested in various cities in India calling the provisions regressive and in violation of the Supreme Court judgment in 2014.<ref name=\"bittuh1\"/><ref name=\"jyotiratnam\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/transgender-bill-criminalises-community-say-activists-seek-its-overhaul/story-U6hfkKpilq6bxsDAd2WvJI.html | title=Transgender bill criminalises community, say activists; seek its overhaul | date=19 December 2018 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Jyoti, and Ratnam | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817072656/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/transgender-bill-criminalises-community-say-activists-seek-its-overhaul/story-U6hfkKpilq6bxsDAd2WvJI.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The criminalisation of begging under the 2018 bill was to affect transgender persons in India, such as hijras and jogtas who engage in begging as a ritual-custom while some rely on it for livelihood.<ref name =\"indiatoday2017\">{{cite news | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/lgbtq-community-protests-against-transgender-persons-bill-1110328-2017-12-17 | title=LGBTQ community protests against Transgender Persons Bill | date=17 December 2017 | agency=India Today | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Hasan, Ilma | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817092306/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/lgbtq-community-protests-against-transgender-persons-bill-1110328-2017-12-17 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"billreaction1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/trans-activists-up-the-ante-to-challenge-bill/article25945066.ece | title=Trans activists up the ante, to challenge Bill | date=9 January 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Ravi, Sidharth | location=New Delhi}}</ref> It was alleged by critics that the provision of the district screening committee left gaps for incompetence and prejudice.<ref name =\"herald\">{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/opinion/second-edit/transgender-bill-remove-709703.html | title=Transgender Bill: remove drawbacks | date=24 December 2018 | agency=Deccan Herald | accessdate=19 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030729/https://www.deccanherald.com/opinion/second-edit/transgender-bill-remove-709703.html | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' reported that even if the provision of a district screening committee existed to prevent imposters from seeking benefits of government welfare schemes, such an arrangement cannot be made at the expense of transgender persons' right to self-determination.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/editorials/transgender-rights-should-not-depend-on-a-screening/story-c1oqqLOTEzSAfyBoV0fWWN.html | title=Transgender rights should not depend on a screening | date=19 February 2018 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=19 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030729/https://www.hindustantimes.com/editorials/transgender-rights-should-not-depend-on-a-screening/story-c1oqqLOTEzSAfyBoV0fWWN.html | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The definition of transgender persons under the 2018 bill, retained by the 2019 act, was reported by ''[[Frontline]]'' to be at variance with international expert understanding of the term.<ref name =\"frontline\"/>\n\nThe 2018 bill and 2019 act have been met with protests by transgender persons.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/dec/22/1k-trans-people-from-pondy-tn-protest-against-new-law-1914889.html | title=Over 1,000 transgenders from Pondicherry, Tamil Nadu protest against new law | date=22 December 2018 | agency=New Indian Express | accessdate=19 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030732/http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/dec/22/1k-trans-people-from-pondy-tn-protest-against-new-law-1914889.html | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Their passing by the parliament has been referred to some transgender persons as \"black day\" and \"gender justice murder day\".<ref name= \"despite\"/><ref name = \"scroll\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/aug/08/transgender-persons-bill-evokes-mixed-responses-2015785.html | title=Transgender Persons Bill evokes mixed responses | date=8 August 2019 | agency=The New Indian Express | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Gowda, Varsha | location=Bengaluru | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103657/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/aug/08/transgender-persons-bill-evokes-mixed-responses-2015785.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Yet others described them as \"draconian and discriminatory\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/bill-will-deprive-us-of-right-to-live-with-dignity-say-transgender-activists/article25837198.ece |title=Bill will deprive us of right to live with dignity, say transgender activists |last=Karangutkar |first=Suyash |date=27 December 2018 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref> After the 2018 bill was passed by the Lok Sabha in December 2018, members of the opposition in Rajya Sabha had stated they will not let the bill pass in its present form in Rajya Sabha.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/latest/907430/transgender-persons-bill-opposition-mps-in-rajya-sabha-promise-not-to-pass-draft-law | title=Transgender Persons Bill: Opposition MPs in Rajya Sabha promise not to pass draft law | date=28 December 2018 | agency=Scroll | accessdate=17 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103316/https://scroll.in/latest/907430/transgender-persons-bill-opposition-mps-in-rajya-sabha-promise-not-to-pass-draft-law | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Protestors alleged the 2018 bill to be institutionalising violence and claimed neglect of recommendations made by the standing committee and transgender persons.<ref name=\"hubbali\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/withdraw-transgenders-bill-table-it-again-with-changes/article25875808.ece |title=\u2018Withdraw Transgenders Bill, table it again with changes\u2019  |date=1 January 2019 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref> Transgender persons called for applications to the district magistrate for issuance of transgender certificates, lesser punishment for crimes against transgender persons, and absence of provisions on mandatory reservations for transgender persons regressive to the judicial mandate of the Supreme Court in 2014 in ''NALSA v. UOI'', thereby violating right to equality and other fundamental rights of transgender persons.<ref name=\"hubbali\"/><ref name=\"newsminute2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/trans-bill-2019-passed-lok-sabha-why-trans-community-india-rejecting-it-106695 | title=Trans Bill 2019 passed in Lok Sabha: Why the trans community in India is rejecting it | date=5 August 2019 | agency=The News Minute | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Dharmadhikari, Sanyukta | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817074728/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/trans-bill-2019-passed-lok-sabha-why-trans-community-india-rejecting-it-106695 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nOn 24 November 2019, two days before the 2019 act was passed by the parliament, protests were staged by the queer community in New Delhi and [[Bengaluru]] as part of the [[Delhi Queer Pride Parade|Delhi queer pride parade]] and the [[Bengaluru Namma Pride March]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/namma-pride-march-rainbow-spreads-cheer-but-with-a-dash-of-black/articleshow/72216384.cms | title=Namma Pride March: Rainbow spread cheer, but with a dash of black | date=25 November 2019 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Iyer, Swathy R | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191129065826/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/namma-pride-march-rainbow-spreads-cheer-but-with-a-dash-of-black/articleshow/72216384.cms | archive-date=29 November 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/delhi-marched-against-trans-bill-2019-on-pride-day-779641.html | title=Delhi marched against Trans Bill 2019 on Pride Day | date=25 November 2019 | agency=Deccan Herald | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Banerjee, Rohini | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123135718/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/delhi-marched-against-trans-bill-2019-on-pride-day-779641.html | archive-date=23 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"jaya\">{{Cite news |last=Pathak |first=Sushmita |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/12/04/784398783/india-just-passed-a-trans-rights-bill-why-are-trans-activists-protesting-it |title=India Just Passed A Trans Rights Bill. Why Are Trans Activists Protesting It? |date=4 December 2019 |work=National Public Radio |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303211742/https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/12/04/784398783/india-just-passed-a-trans-rights-bill-why-are-trans-activists-protesting-it |archive-date=3 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The legislation also drew criticism from the [[All India Mahila Congress]] and opposition from parliamentarians including [[Jaya Bachchan]] and [[Sasmit Patra]], while [[Derek O\u2019Brien]] and Tiruchi Siva also expressed their concerns before the house.<ref name=\"jaya2\"/><ref name=\"jaya\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/a-bill-meant-to-protect-indias-transgender-community-instead-leaves-them-angry-and-aggrieved/2019/11/29/6c2c7b7e-116b-11ea-924c-b34d09bbc948_story.html | title=A bill meant to protect India\u2019s transgender community instead leaves them angry and aggrieved | date=30 November 2019 | agency=The Washington Post | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Masih, Niha | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302034520/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/a-bill-meant-to-protect-indias-transgender-community-instead-leaves-them-angry-and-aggrieved/2019/11/29/6c2c7b7e-116b-11ea-924c-b34d09bbc948_story.html | archive-date=2 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> After the legislation was passed by the parliament, transgender persons and activists protested against the legislation, organised meetings to address the situation, and urged the president not to sign and assent to the bill.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/mumbai/other/protests-held-in-dadar-against-transgender-persons-bill-2019/articleshow/72309119.cms | title=Protests held in Dadar against Transgender Persons Bill 2019 | work=Mumbai Mirror | date=1 December 2019 | accessdate=17 April 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191201051151/https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/mumbai/other/protests-held-in-dadar-against-transgender-persons-bill-2019/articleshow/72309119.cms | archive-date=1 December 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"jaya\"/> <ref>{{Cite news |last=Khan |first=Fatima |url=https://theprint.in/india/murder-of-gender-justice-activists-urge-president-kovind-not-to-sign-transgender-bill/327360/ |title=\u2018Murder of gender justice\u2019 \u2014 activists urge President Kovind not to sign transgender bill |date=27 November 2019 |work=The Print |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191201121026/https://theprint.in/india/murder-of-gender-justice-activists-urge-president-kovind-not-to-sign-transgender-bill/327360/ |archive-date=1 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> There were also protests by the queer community against the act as part of the [[Queer Azaadi Mumbai|Mumbai pride parade]], in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/take-back-trans-act-mumbai-trans-community/1726557 | title=Take back Trans Act: Mumbai Trans community | work=Outlook | date=5 February 2020 | agency=IANS | accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/mumbai-pride-2020-thousands-stand-in-solidarity-with-queer-muslims-amid-caa-nrc-chaos-urge-govt-to-amend-draconian-transgender-act-7991111.html | title=Mumbai Pride 2020: Thousands stand in solidarity with queer Muslims amid CAA-NRC chaos, urge govt to amend 'draconian' Transgender Act | work=Firstpost | date=25 February 2020 | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Manral, Avnisha | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315122340/https://www.firstpost.com/india/mumbai-pride-2020-thousands-stand-in-solidarity-with-queer-muslims-amid-caa-nrc-chaos-urge-govt-to-amend-draconian-transgender-act-7991111.html | archive-date=15 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe legislation has been criticised by [[Human Rights Watch]] and the [[International Commission of Jurists]].<ref name=\"jurists\">{{Cite news |last=Sharma |first=Neetu Chandra |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-protection-of-rights-bill-2019-11574774522034.html |title=Rajya Sabha passes Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2019 |date=26 November 2019 |work=Live Mint |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128004011/https://www.livemint.com/news/india/rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-protection-of-rights-bill-2019-11574774522034.html |archive-date=28 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"hrw\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/07/23/india-transgender-bill-raises-rights-concerns | title=India: Transgender Bill Raises Rights Concerns | date=23 July 2019 | agency=Human Rights Watch | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New York | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730050854/https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/07/23/india-transgender-bill-raises-rights-concerns | archive-date=30 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> In the run-up to the 2019 general elections to the Lok Sabha, Indian National Congress had promised in its electoral manifesto to withdraw the 2018 bill and introduce a new one, in consultation with members of the queer community.<ref name = \"manifesto\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thestatesman.com/elections-2019/congress-releases-poll-manifesto-promises-jobs-benefits-farmers-niti-aayog-1502742568.html | title=Congress manifesto promises 34 lakh jobs, farmer welfare, says will scrap NITI Aayog | date=2 April 2019 | agency=The Statesman | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=SNS Web | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817134723/https://www.thestatesman.com/elections-2019/congress-releases-poll-manifesto-promises-jobs-benefits-farmers-niti-aayog-1502742568.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The Communist Party of India (Marxist) had supported the passing of the 2014 bill in its electoral manifesto.<ref name = \"manifesto\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/elections/lok-sabha-2019/the-invisible-third-gender-voters/article26764806.ece | title=The invisible \u2018third gender\u2019 voters | date=8 April 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Rosario, Kennith | location=Mumbai}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 January 2020, the Supreme Court issued a notice to the central government in a petition filed by advocate and transgender rights activist, Swati Bidhan Baruah, challenging the constitutionality of the 2019 legislation.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/supreme-court-notice-to-centre-on-plea-against-transgender-act/story-HfBrPZBTFmusm9theecWoL.html | title=Supreme Court notice to Centre on plea against transgender act | work=Hindustan Times | date=28 January 2020 | accessdate=17 April 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129045020/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/supreme-court-notice-to-centre-on-plea-against-transgender-act/story-HfBrPZBTFmusm9theecWoL.html | archive-date=29 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/supreme-court-notice-to-centre-on-plea-against-transgender-act-2019-798774.html | title=Supreme Court notice to Centre on plea against Transgender Act, 2019| work=Deccan Herald | date=27 January 2020 | agency=Tripathi, Ashish | accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[LGBT rights in India]]\n*[[Human rights in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019}}\n* [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Expert_Committee_Report_%282014%29_1.pdf   Report of the Expert Committee on Issues Relating to Transgender Persons (27 January 2014)]\n* [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Transgender_Bill%2C_2015_-_PMB_passed_in_RS_2.pdf   The Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014]\n* [http://socialjustice.nic.in/writereaddata/UploadFile/TG%20bill%20gazette.pdf The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019]\n* [http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2020/215301.pdf  Notification dated 10 January 2020 commencing the provisions of the act]\n\n{{Indian legislation}}\n{{LGBT in India}}\n{{Transgender topics}}\n\n[[Category:LGBT rights in India]]\n[[Category:Modi administration]]\n[[Category:Transgender law]]\n[[Category:2019 in Indian law]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Act of the Parliament of India}}\n\n{{Distinguish|Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox legislation\n| short_title = The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019\n| legislature =\n| image =\n| imagesize = 100\n| imagealt = Emblem of India\n| long_title = An Act to provide for protection of rights of transgender persons and their welfare and for matters connected therewith and incidental thereto.\n| citation =\n| territorial_extent = [[Republic of India]]\n| enacted_by = [[Parliament of India]]\n| date_passed = 5 August 2019\n| date_passed2 = 26 November 2019\n| date_assented = 5 December 2019\n| date_signed = 5 December 2019\n| date_commenced = 10 January 2020\n| bill =\n\n| bill_citation = Bill No. 169 of 2019\n| act_citation = Act No. 40 of 2019\n[http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/The%20Transgender%20Persons%20%28Protection%20of%20Rights%29%20Bill%2C%202019%20Bill%20Text.pdf]\n| bill_date = 19 July 2019\n| introduced_by = Minister for Social Justice and Empowerment\n| 1st_reading = 5 August 2019\n| 2nd_reading =\n| 3rd_reading =\n| white_paper =\n| committee_report = [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/SCR-%20Transgender%20Bill.pdf   43rd Report by Standing Committee on Social Justice and Empowerment, July 2017]\n| amendments =\n| repeals =\n| related = [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Transgender%20persons%20bill%20as%20passed%20by%20LS.pdf        The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2018]<br/>[http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Transgender_Persons_Bill%2C_2016_1.pdf  The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2016]<br/>[[Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014|The Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014]]\n| summary =\n| keywords =\n| status = In force\n\n}}\n\nThe '''Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019''' is an [[Act (law)|act]] of the [[Parliament of India]] with the objective to provide for protection of rights of [[Transgender|transgender persons]], their welfare, and other related matters. The act was introduced in the [[Lok Sabha]], the lower house of the Parliament, on 19 July 2019 by the [[Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment|Minister of Social Justice and Empowerment]], [[Thawar Chand Gehlot]], in light of the lapse of the Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2018. The 2019 act and the immediately preceding 2018 bill, were both preceded by a 2016 version,. They were met with protests and criticism by transgender persons, lawyers, and activists in India. The 2016 bill was sent to a [[Standing committee (India)|standing committee]] which submitted its report in July  2017. Following this, the Lok Sabha tabled and passed a newer version of the bill in December 2018. However, it did not incorporate many of the committee's recommendations. Although members of the opposition criticised the 2019 act and assured transgender persons of not voting in favour of it, it was passed by the Lok Sabha on 5 August 2019 and by the [[Rajya Sabha]], the upper house of the Parliament, on 26 November 2019. The [[President of India|president]] assented to it on 5 December 2019, upon which the act was notified in the ''[[Gazette of India]]''. It was brought into effect from 10 January 2020 onwards vide a notification in the ''Gazette'' on the same day.\n\nFollowing protests by the [[LGBT|queer community]] against the 2016 and 2018 bills, the 2019 act has done away with few of the severely criticised provisions of the 2018 bill, such as criminalisation of begging and the establishment of a district screening committee to process applications for issuance of transgender person certificates. However, it fails to incorporate yet other principles in line with the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] judgment in ''[[National Legal Services Authority v. Union of India]]'' (''NALSA v. UOI'') in 2014, such as the right of transgender persons to self-perceived gender identity without undergoing [[sex reassignment surgery]], and mandatory reservations in jobs and educational institutions. The act has also been criticised for the lesser punishment for crimes against transgender persons compared with punishment for crimes against [[cisgender|cisgender persons]]. On 27 January 2020, the Supreme Court issued a notice to the central government in a petition filed challenging the constitutionality of the 2019 legislation\n\nIn January 2014, while judicial pronouncement in the ''NALSA'' petition was pending, the ministry had published an Expert Committee Report on issues relating to transgender persons, after consultations with transgender persons. [[Tiruchi Siva]], of the [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]] party, had introduced the [[Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014|Rights of Transgender Persons Bill]] in 2014, in the Rajya Sabha, which was passed by the house in 2015. The 2014 bill contains provisions progressive to those in the bills introduced in between 2016 and 2019, but has been pending in the Lok Sabha since 2015. Prior to the [[Indian general elections, 2019|2019 general elections]], parties such as the [[Indian National Congress]] and [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] had promised in their respective electoral manifestoes to, respectively, withdraw the 2018 bill \u2014 while introducing a new one consulting members of the queer community \u2014 and pass the 2014 bill.\n\n==History and background==\n[[File:Hijra and companions in Eastern Bengal.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Hijras in eastern Bengal, ''circa'' 1860]]\n{{LGBT rights}}\nIn 2014, the Supreme Court of India delivered its judgment in ''National Legal Services Authority v. Union of India'' (also known as, ''NALSA v. UOI''), in which it recognised the rights of the transgender persons in India and laid down a series of measures for securing transgender persons' rights by mandating prohibition of discrimination, recommending the creation of welfare policies and reservations for transgender persons in educational institutions and jobs.<ref name=\"th1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/supreme-court-recognises-transgenders-as-third-gender/article5914572.ece | title=Supreme Court recognises transgenders as third gender | date=15 April 2014 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Venkatesan, J. | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614152049/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/supreme-court-recognises-transgenders-as-third-gender/article5914572.ece | archive-date=14 June 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> The judgment upheld the right of a transgender person to self-perceived gender identity, guaranteed by the [[Constitution of India]], in the absence of sex reassignment surgery.<ref name=\"th2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/a-promise-falls-short/article23505892.ece | title=A promise falls short | date=12 April 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kothari, Jayna}}</ref> The 2014 judicial mandate stands backed by the judgments of the Supreme Court in ''[[Justice K. S. Puttaswamy (Retd.) and Anr. vs Union Of India And Ors.|Justice K. S. Puttaswamy (Retd.) and anr. v. Union of India and ors.]]'' (2017) and ''[[Navtej Singh Johar v. Union of India]]'' (2018).<ref name=\"th3\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/the-supreme-court-trans-formed/article24949441.ece | title=The Supreme Court trans-formed | date=15 September 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kothari, Jayna}}</ref> The judgment in ''NALSA v. UOI'' also noted the presence of transgender persons in India throughout its history, and made reference to the [[Hijra (South Asia)|hijra, kinnar, and jogta]] communities, spread across the country and beyond in the [[Indian subcontinent]].<ref>{{cite journal | title=National Legal Services Authority versus Union of India and others | journal=Supreme Court Cases | year=2014 | volume=5 | pages=438}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-27031180 | title=India court recognises transgender people as third gender | date=15 April 2014 | agency=BBC | accessdate=17 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811110426/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-27031180 | archive-date=11 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile the decision in the ''NALSA'' petition was still pending, an expert committee report on issues relating to transgender persons was published in January 2014, after consultations by the Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment with transgender persons in August 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/rights-wrongs/article21339721.ece | title=Rights & wrongs \u2014 on Transgender Persons Bill | date=9 December 2017 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625123619/http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/rights-wrongs/article21339721.ece | archive-date=25 June 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/expert-panel-wants-transgender-declared-third-gender/article5781874.ece | title=Expert panel wants transgender declared third gender | date=24 March 2014 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Dhar, Aarti | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224013224/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/expert-panel-wants-transgender-declared-third-gender/article5781874.ece | archive-date=24 December 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> In this background, Tiruchi Siva of the Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam party introduced a [[private member's bill]] in the Rajya Sabha, namely the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill (No.  XLIXC-C), 2014.<ref name =\"transpvt\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/rajya-sabha-passes-private-bill-on-transgenders/article7138056.ece | title=RS passes Bill on transgender rights | date=24 April 2015 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Gandhi and, Ramachandran | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510072419/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/rajya-sabha-passes-private-bill-on-transgenders/article7138056.ece | archive-date=10 May 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe government had initially asked him to withdraw the bill citing various anomalies; however, the opposition had a majority in the house and the bill was unanimously passed by the Rajya Sabha on 24 April 2015.<ref name=\"transpvt\" /> The bill was welcomed by queer rights activists in India.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/turning-point-in-transgender-rights/article7139875.ece | title=\"Turning point in transgender rights\" | date=25 April 2015 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Srinivasan, Meera | location=Chennai}}</ref> However, some transgender persons noted their absence in the entire process and called for their recommendations being sought for.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/activists-oppose-bill-on-transgender-rights/article7993938.ece | title=Activists oppose Bill on transgender rights | date=16 December 2015 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=Bengaluru}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/cant-erase-hijra-culture-transgender-persons-bill-1581247-2019-08-16 | title=\"We can't erase our hijra culture\" | date=16 August 2019 | agency=India Today | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Sinha, Chinki | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816153625/https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/cant-erase-hijra-culture-transgender-persons-bill-1581247-2019-08-16 | archive-date=16 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Following the passing of the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014 in 2015, it stood to be the first private member's bill to be passed by the Rajya Sabha in the preceding thirty-six years<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Rajya-Sabha-passes-first-private-members-bill-in-36-years-on-transgenders-rights/articleshow/47039967.cms | title=Rajya Sabha passes first private member's bill in 36 years, on transgenders' rights | date=25 April 2015 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831081935/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Rajya-Sabha-passes-first-private-members-bill-in-36-years-on-transgenders-rights/articleshow/47039967.cms | archive-date=31 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> and by the Parliament in the preceding forty-five years.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rajya-sabha-private-member-bill-transgenders-rights-250096-2015-04-24 | title=Rajya Sabha passes transgenders rights bill, first private member proposal in 46 years | date=24 April 2015 | agency=India Today | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817114840/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rajya-sabha-private-member-bill-transgenders-rights-250096-2015-04-24 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Until 2015, only sixteen private member's bills had stood passed since 1947.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Just-14-private-members-bills-passed-by-Parliament-till-date-the-last-was-in-1970/articleshow/47046338.cms | title=Just 14 private member's bill passed by Parliament till date; the last was in 1970 | date=25 April 2015 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907004217/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Just-14-private-members-bills-passed-by-Parliament-till-date-the-last-was-in-1970/articleshow/47046338.cms | archive-date=7 September 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe 2014 bill underwent significant changes when the government drafted its own version of the bill, with omissions of provisions in the 2014 bill.<ref name = \"2015bill\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/all-you-need-to-know-about-the-transgender-persons-bill-2016/article21226710.ece | title=All you need to know about the Transgender Persons Bill, 2016 | date=30 November 2017 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Abraham, Rohan | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507193832/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/all-you-need-to-know-about-the-transgender-persons-bill-2016/article21226710.ece | archive-date=7 May 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> After recommendations were received from transgender persons, the bill was sent to the [[Ministry of Law and Justice (India)|Ministry of Law and Justice]].<ref name = \"2015bill\"/> It came to be known as the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2015.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bill-ensures-family-life-for-transgender-children/articleshow/50374808.cms | title=Bill ensures family life for transgender children | date=30 December 2015 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=19 August 2019 | author=Ghildiyal, Subodh | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901033429/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bill-ensures-family-life-for-transgender-children/articleshow/50374808.cms | archive-date=1 September 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Later, on 26 February 2016, the bill was introduced in the Lok Sabha for debate by [[Baijayant Panda]] of the [[Biju Janata Dal]] party.<ref name=\"bjd\">{{cite news | url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/lok-sabha-takes-up-bill-to-end-transgender-discrimination-1281768 | title=Lok Sabha Takes Up Bill To End Transgender Discrimination | date=27 February 2016 | agency=NDTV | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=PTI | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817124856/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/lok-sabha-takes-up-bill-to-end-transgender-discrimination-1281768 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> He argued that the bill would help extend constitutional rights and end the discrimination against transgender people, allowing them to live a life of dignity.<ref name=\"bjd\"/> The bill was discussed in the Lok Sabha on 29 April 2016.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/live-today-in-parliament-april-29-2016/article8536287.ece | title=Lok Sabha discusses transgender rights | date=29 April 2016 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> Siva stated that he will not be withdrawing the 2014 bill.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/article/906587/how-parliament-came-to-have-two-bills-on-transgender-persons-rights-and-why-neither-may-pass | title=How Parliament came to have two Bills on transgender persons\u2019 rights (and why neither may pass) | date=24 December 2018 | agency=Scroll | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Lalwani, Vijayta | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103306/https://scroll.in/article/906587/how-parliament-came-to-have-two-bills-on-transgender-persons-rights-and-why-neither-may-pass | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile the 2014 bill passed by the Rajya Sabha continues to be pending,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/rajya-sabha-member-wants-to-modify-national-anthem/article28100859.ece | title=Rajya Sabha member wants to modify National Anthem | date=21 June 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> the government tabled the Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill (No. 210), 2016, on 2 August 2016, following the constitution of the Lok Sabha, post the [[Indian general elections, 2014|2014 general elections]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/explained-why-the-citizenship-amendment-bill-is-dead-for-now-5582573/ | title=Explained: Why the Citizenship Amendment Bill is dead, for now | date=13 February 2019 | agency=Indian Express | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817130024/https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/explained-why-the-citizenship-amendment-bill-is-dead-for-now-5582573/ | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The 2016 bill had various provisions regressive to the provisions in the 2014 bill.<ref name=\"scroll\">{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/article/906205/this-is-a-black-day-activists-criticise-transgender-persons-bill-passed-in-lok-sabha | title=\u2018This is a black day\u2019: Activists criticise Transgender Persons Bill passed in Lok Sabha | date=19 December 2018 | agency=Scroll | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Lalwani, Vijayta | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103231/https://scroll.in/article/906205/this-is-a-black-day-activists-criticise-transgender-persons-bill-passed-in-lok-sabha | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"jyotiratnam\" /> The bill was met with criticism and protests from Indian transgender persons and was referred to the standing committee, which submitted its report in July 2018.<ref name=\"jyotiratnam\" /> The Lok Sabha tabled and passed a newer version of the bill with twenty-seven amendments on 17 December 2018.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://ptinews.com/news/10250267_Lok-Sabha-passes-Transgender-bill.html | title=Lok Sabha passes Transgender bill | date=17 December 2018 | agency=PRI | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817092137/http://ptinews.com/news/10250267_Lok-Sabha-passes-Transgender-bill.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"bittuh1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-transgender-persons-bill-misses-key-demands-of-the-community/story-0c6VV1GvYuV4xqYL06zw8N.html | title=The Transgender Persons Bill misses key demands of the community | date=15 June 2019 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kondaiah, Karthik Bittu | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817053704/https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-transgender-persons-bill-misses-key-demands-of-the-community/story-0c6VV1GvYuV4xqYL06zw8N.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The bill was once again met with severe criticism and protests pan-India, as it overlooked the recommendations made by the standing committee and suggestions offered by transgender persons.<ref name=\"revised\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/colleges-join-hands-to-protest-against-transgender-bill-2018/article25844976.ece | title=Colleges join hands to protest against Transgender Bill 2018 | date=28 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Karangutkar, Suyash | location=Mumbai}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/rights-revised/article25783926.ece | title=Rights, revised: on the Transgender Persons Bill, 2018 | date=20 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> However, the 2018 bill stood lapsed.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-rights-bill-to-be-reintroduced/article27474400.ece | title=Transgender rights Bill to be reintroduced | date=5 June 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the constitution of the Lok Sabha, post the 2019 general elections, the bill was reintroduced on 19 July 2019 by the Minister of Social Justice and Empowerment, [[Thawar Chand Gehlot]]<ref name=\"leaflet1\">{{cite news | url=https://theleaflet.in/transgender-bill-introduced-in-the-lok-sabha/ | title=Transgender Bill introduced in the Lok Sabha | date=24 July 2019 | agency=The Leaflet | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Sirohi, Nishant | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817092851/https://theleaflet.in/transgender-bill-introduced-in-the-lok-sabha/ | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Before this the bill had been approved by the [[Cabinet of India|union cabinet]] on 10 July 2019.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/cabinet-approves-transgender-bill/article28355950.ece | title=Cabinet approves transgender bill | work=The Hindu Business Line | date=10 July 2019 | agency=Press Trust of India | accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> The bill was passed by a voice vote in the Lok Sabha on 5 August 2019, amidst commotion on the house following the revocation of Jammu and Kashmir's special status by the Parliament on the same day.<ref name=\"passedaugust\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-persons-bill-passed-in-lok-sabha/article28822000.ece | title=Transgender Persons bill passed in Lok Sabha | date=5 August 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=PTI | location=New Delhi}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/congress-opposition-parties-protest-in-lok-sabha-seek-presence-of-prime-minister-on-kashmir-decisions/articleshow/70536012.cms | title=Congress opposition parties protest in Lok Sabha seek presence of Prime Minister on Kashmir decision | date=5 August 2019 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808023548/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/congress-opposition-parties-protest-in-lok-sabha-seek-presence-of-prime-minister-on-kashmir-decisions/articleshow/70536012.cms | archive-date=8 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The bill was introduced in the Rajya Sabha by Thawarchand Gehlot on 20 November 2019, upon which it was passed without any amendments on 26 November 2019 following a motion to refer it to a [[Select_committee#India|select committee]] that failed by 77 noes against 55 ayes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/parliament-passes-bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders/article30087790.ece |title=Parliament passes Bill to protect rights of transgenders |work=26 November 2019 |access-date=17 April 2020 |publisher=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130183741/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/parliament-passes-bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders/article30087790.ece |archive-date=30 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name =\"jaya2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/amid-opposition-trans-community-rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-bill-112971 |title=Amid opposition from trans community, Rajya Sabha passes Transgender Persons Bill |date=26 November 2019 |work=The News Minute |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414175331/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/amid-opposition-trans-community-rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-bill-112971 |archive-date=14 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/rajya-sabha-passes-criticised-transgender-rights-bill |title=Rajya Sabha Passes Controversial Transgender Rights Bill |date=26 November 2019 |work=The Wire |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128190253/https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/rajya-sabha-passes-criticised-transgender-rights-bill |archive-date=28 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The bill received presidential assent on 5 December 2019, following which the Ministry of Law and Justice notified it in the ''Gazette of India'' as Act No. 40 of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://socialjustice.nic.in/writereaddata/UploadFile/TG%20bill%20gazette.pdf |title=The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019 [No. 40 of 2019] |date=5 December 2019 |website=socialjustice.nic.in |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412014303/http://socialjustice.nic.in/writereaddata/UploadFile/TG%20bill%20gazette.pdf |archive-date=12 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name= \"despite\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/despite-massive-protests-trans-bill-gets-president-s-assent-becomes-law-113643 |title=Despite massive protests, Trans Bill gets President\u2019s assent, becomes law |date=7 December 2019 |work=The News Minute |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304050316/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/despite-massive-protests-trans-bill-gets-president-s-assent-becomes-law-113643 |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The act came into effect from 10 January 2020 onwards vide a notification in the ''Gazette'' on the same day by the Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2020/215301.pdf |title=Notification, Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment |date=10 January 2020 |website=egazette.nic.in |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111034026/http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2020/215301.pdf |archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Nath |first=Damini |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-persons-act-comes-into-effect/article30545336.ece |title=Transgender Persons Act comes into effect |date=11 January 2020 |work=The Hindu |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229091631/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-persons-act-comes-into-effect/article30545336.ece |archive-date=29 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Statutory provisions==\nThe 2018 bill had criminalised begging \u2014 which transgender persons in India, such as the hijras and jogtas, engage in as a ritual-custom while some rely on it for livelihood \u2014 apart from mandating applications made to the [[District magistrate (India)|district magistrate]] to be screened through a district screening committee for issuance of transgender person certificates.<ref name =\"indiatoday2017\"/><ref name=\"billreaction1\"/> The screening committee was to be composed of five people including a chief medical officer, district social welfare officer, psychologist/psychiatrist, and a representative of the transgender persons<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.prsindia.org/billtrack/transgender-persons-protection-rights-bill-2016 | title=The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2016 | publisher=PRS Legislative Research | accessdate=19 August 2019 | author=PRS India | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819031027/http://www.prsindia.org/billtrack/transgender-persons-protection-rights-bill-2016 | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/against-the-mandate-for-inclusion/article25791080.ece | title=Against the mandate for inclusion: the Transgender Persons Bill 2018 | date=21 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=19 August 2019 | author=Banerjie, Ajita}}</ref> The 2018 bill had also not provided for mandatory reservations for transgender persons and mandated lower punishment for crimes against transgender persons, as compared to punishment for crimes against cisgender persons under the [[Indian Penal Code]].<ref name =\"jyotiratnam\"/><ref name=\"bittuh1\"/> It also ensured a family-life for transgender children, by prohibiting their separation from their family, without taking into account harassment and discrimination they may face within their family as a result of which they may choose to be separated and reside with transgender persons.<ref name = \"herald\"/><ref name = \"economic\"/> A transgender child, as per the provisions, could be separated from their family only by a court order.<ref name = \"revised\"/> The 2018 bill provided for undergoing sex reassignment surgery as a mandatory pre-requirement to be identified as male or female.<ref name =\"frontline\">{{Cite news |url=https://frontline.thehindu.com/dispatches/article25957990.ece |title=Stiff opposition to transgender persons Bill |last=Venkatesan |first=V. |date=10 January 2019 |work=Frontline |access-date=20 September 2019 |last2=Kaur |first2=Tanveer}}</ref> The 2019 act does away only with few of the criticised provisions of the 2018 bill, such as the district screening committee and the criminalisation of begging.<ref name=\"reuters1\"/>\n\nThe statutory provisions of the 2019 act prohibit discrimination against transgender persons.<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-lgbt-lawmaking/india-introduces-new-trans-rights-bill-in-parliament-after-backlash-idUSKCN1UE28S | title=India introduces new trans rights bill in parliament after backlash | date=19 July 2019 | agency=Reuters | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Banerji, Annie | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817074604/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-lgbt-lawmaking/india-introduces-new-trans-rights-bill-in-parliament-after-backlash-idUSKCN1UE28S | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Similar to the 2018 bill, the 2019 act includes [[intersex|intersex persons]], hijras, jogtas, and [[kinnar]]s within its definition of transgender persons,<ref name =\"frontline\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/govt-making-rules-for-us-without-us-transgenders/article29104679.ece | title=Govt. making rules for us without us: transgenders | date=16 August 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Aggarwal, Aarushi | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815231759/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/govt-making-rules-for-us-without-us-transgenders/article29104679.ece | archive-date=15 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> though it does not define terms such as trans-man, trans-woman, and [[genderqueer]].<ref name =\"frontline\"/><ref name=\"tribune1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/comment/bringing-transgenders-into-mainstream/807918.html |title=Bringing transgenders into mainstream |last=Quraishi |first=S. Y. |date=26 July 2019 |work=The Tribune |accessdate=17 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817104013/https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/comment/bringing-transgenders-into-mainstream/807918.html |archive-date=17 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Both, the 2019 act as well as the 2018 bill, describe a transgender person as someone whose gender does not match with the gender assigned to them at birth.<ref name =\"frontline\"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/The%20Transgender%20Persons%20%28Protection%20of%20Rights%29%20Bill%2C%202019%20Bill%20Text.pdf |title=The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill (No. 169), 2019 |work=PRS Legislative Research |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nUnder the provisions of the 2019 act, a transgender person can apply to the district magistrate for a transgender person certificate which will give them the right to change the name on their birth certificate and have all documents updated accordingly.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/transgender-rights-bill-a-stunted-understanding-of-gender-and-equality | title=Transgender Rights Bill: A Stunted Understanding of Gender and Equality | date=5 August 2019 | agency=The Wire | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Gandhi, and Ghia | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802165656/https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/transgender-rights-bill-a-stunted-understanding-of-gender-and-equality | archive-date=2 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> However, similar to the 2018 bill provisions, a transgender person can be identified as male or female only after applying for a revised certificate to the district magistrate, post sex reassignment surgery.<ref name=\"newsminute1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/why-transgender-persons-bill-2018-public-health-nightmare-community-94206 | title=Why Transgender Persons Bill 2018 is a healthcare nightmare for the community | date=30 December 2018 | agency=The News Minute | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Karpagam, Sylvia | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817074604/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/why-transgender-persons-bill-2018-public-health-nightmare-community-94206 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe 2019 act also protects transgender children and provides for states and institutions to come up with adequate policies for the welfare of transgender persons.<ref name=\"dh\">{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders-passed-in-ls-752193.html | title=Bill to protect rights of transgenders passed in LS | date=5 August 2019 | agency=Deccan Herald | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kumar, Prakash | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817095008/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders-passed-in-ls-752193.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name = \"economic\">{{cite news | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/transgender-rights-bill-introduced-in-lok-sabha-may-be-taken-up-next-week/articleshow/70301454.cms | title=Transgender Rights Bill introduced in Lok Sabha, may be taken up next week | date=20 July 2019 | agency=Economic Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Sharma, Nidhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817094010/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/transgender-rights-bill-introduced-in-lok-sabha-may-be-taken-up-next-week/articleshow/70301454.cms | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Similar to the provisions of the 2018 bill, under the provisions of the 2019 act a transgender child can be separated from their family by a court order.<ref name = \"revised\"/> However, unlike the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014 neither the 2018 nor the 2019 act provide for mandatory reservations for transgender persons in educational institutions and jobs.<ref name=\"leaflet1\"/> The 2014 bill had provided for two per-cent reservations in educational institutions and public employment.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/a-law-that-defeats-its-purpose/article25854190.ece | title=A law that defeats its purpose | date=29 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kothari, Jayna}}</ref> Similar to the 2018 bill, the 2019 act provides for punishment for crimes against transgender persons, which stands as an imprisonment for a term not less than six months but which may extend to two years and a fine.<ref name =\"jyotiratnam\"/><ref name =\"tribune1\"/> The 2019 act, as well as the 2018 bill, also provide for the constitution of a National Council for Transgender Persons.<ref name = \"passedaugust\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-lok-sabha-passes-bill-to-prohibit-discrimination-against-transgenders-2779179 | title=Lok Sabha passes bill to prohibit discrimination against transgenders | date=5 August 2019 | agency=DNA | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=ANI | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806145618/https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-lok-sabha-passes-bill-to-prohibit-discrimination-against-transgenders-2779179 | archive-date=6 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism and reactions==\n[[File:Protest against Transgender Bill in Mumbai, India.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Protests against the 2018 bill in [[Mumbai]], in December 2018]]\nThe 2018 bill passed by the Lok Sabha was widely criticised by transgender persons, activists, students, and lawyers.<ref name=\"gautamh1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-rajya-sabha-must-amend-the-transgender-persons-bill/story-WEyPFztPVABpfaQyDYBt5I.html | title=The Rajya Sabha must amend the Transgender Persons Bill | date=5 January 2019 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Bhatia, Gautam | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817073521/https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-rajya-sabha-must-amend-the-transgender-persons-bill/story-WEyPFztPVABpfaQyDYBt5I.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Transgender persons protested in various cities in India calling the provisions regressive and in violation of the Supreme Court judgment in 2014.<ref name=\"bittuh1\"/><ref name=\"jyotiratnam\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/transgender-bill-criminalises-community-say-activists-seek-its-overhaul/story-U6hfkKpilq6bxsDAd2WvJI.html | title=Transgender bill criminalises community, say activists; seek its overhaul | date=19 December 2018 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Jyoti, and Ratnam | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817072656/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/transgender-bill-criminalises-community-say-activists-seek-its-overhaul/story-U6hfkKpilq6bxsDAd2WvJI.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The criminalisation of begging under the 2018 bill was to affect transgender persons in India, such as hijras and jogtas who engage in begging as a ritual-custom while some rely on it for livelihood.<ref name =\"indiatoday2017\">{{cite news | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/lgbtq-community-protests-against-transgender-persons-bill-1110328-2017-12-17 | title=LGBTQ community protests against Transgender Persons Bill | date=17 December 2017 | agency=India Today | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Hasan, Ilma | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817092306/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/lgbtq-community-protests-against-transgender-persons-bill-1110328-2017-12-17 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"billreaction1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/trans-activists-up-the-ante-to-challenge-bill/article25945066.ece | title=Trans activists up the ante, to challenge Bill | date=9 January 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Ravi, Sidharth | location=New Delhi}}</ref> It was alleged by critics that the provision of the district screening committee left gaps for incompetence and prejudice.<ref name =\"herald\">{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/opinion/second-edit/transgender-bill-remove-709703.html | title=Transgender Bill: remove drawbacks | date=24 December 2018 | agency=Deccan Herald | accessdate=19 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030729/https://www.deccanherald.com/opinion/second-edit/transgender-bill-remove-709703.html | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' reported that even if the provision of a district screening committee existed to prevent imposters from seeking benefits of government welfare schemes, such an arrangement cannot be made at the expense of transgender persons' right to self-determination.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/editorials/transgender-rights-should-not-depend-on-a-screening/story-c1oqqLOTEzSAfyBoV0fWWN.html | title=Transgender rights should not depend on a screening | date=19 February 2018 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=19 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030729/https://www.hindustantimes.com/editorials/transgender-rights-should-not-depend-on-a-screening/story-c1oqqLOTEzSAfyBoV0fWWN.html | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The definition of transgender persons under the 2018 bill, retained by the 2019 act, was reported by ''[[Frontline]]'' to be at variance with international expert understanding of the term.<ref name =\"frontline\"/>\n\nThe 2018 bill and 2019 act have been met with protests by transgender persons.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/dec/22/1k-trans-people-from-pondy-tn-protest-against-new-law-1914889.html | title=Over 1,000 transgenders from Pondicherry, Tamil Nadu protest against new law | date=22 December 2018 | agency=New Indian Express | accessdate=19 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030732/http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/dec/22/1k-trans-people-from-pondy-tn-protest-against-new-law-1914889.html | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Their passing by the parliament has been referred to some transgender persons as \"black day\" and \"gender justice murder day\".<ref name= \"despite\"/><ref name = \"scroll\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/aug/08/transgender-persons-bill-evokes-mixed-responses-2015785.html | title=Transgender Persons Bill evokes mixed responses | date=8 August 2019 | agency=The New Indian Express | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Gowda, Varsha | location=Bengaluru | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103657/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/aug/08/transgender-persons-bill-evokes-mixed-responses-2015785.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Yet others described them as \"draconian and discriminatory\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/bill-will-deprive-us-of-right-to-live-with-dignity-say-transgender-activists/article25837198.ece |title=Bill will deprive us of right to live with dignity, say transgender activists |last=Karangutkar |first=Suyash |date=27 December 2018 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref> After the 2018 bill was passed by the Lok Sabha in December 2018, members of the opposition in Rajya Sabha had stated they will not let the bill pass in its present form in Rajya Sabha.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/latest/907430/transgender-persons-bill-opposition-mps-in-rajya-sabha-promise-not-to-pass-draft-law | title=Transgender Persons Bill: Opposition MPs in Rajya Sabha promise not to pass draft law | date=28 December 2018 | agency=Scroll | accessdate=17 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103316/https://scroll.in/latest/907430/transgender-persons-bill-opposition-mps-in-rajya-sabha-promise-not-to-pass-draft-law | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Protestors alleged the 2018 bill to be institutionalising violence and claimed neglect of recommendations made by the standing committee and transgender persons.<ref name=\"hubbali\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/withdraw-transgenders-bill-table-it-again-with-changes/article25875808.ece |title=\u2018Withdraw Transgenders Bill, table it again with changes\u2019  |date=1 January 2019 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref> Transgender persons called for applications to the district magistrate for issuance of transgender certificates, lesser punishment for crimes against transgender persons, and absence of provisions on mandatory reservations for transgender persons regressive to the judicial mandate of the Supreme Court in 2014 in ''NALSA v. UOI'', thereby violating right to equality and other fundamental rights of transgender persons.<ref name=\"hubbali\"/><ref name=\"newsminute2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/trans-bill-2019-passed-lok-sabha-why-trans-community-india-rejecting-it-106695 | title=Trans Bill 2019 passed in Lok Sabha: Why the trans community in India is rejecting it | date=5 August 2019 | agency=The News Minute | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Dharmadhikari, Sanyukta | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817074728/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/trans-bill-2019-passed-lok-sabha-why-trans-community-india-rejecting-it-106695 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nOn 24 November 2019, two days before the 2019 act was passed by the parliament, protests were staged by the queer community in New Delhi and [[Bengaluru]] as part of the [[Delhi Queer Pride Parade|Delhi queer pride parade]] and the [[Bengaluru Namma Pride March]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/namma-pride-march-rainbow-spreads-cheer-but-with-a-dash-of-black/articleshow/72216384.cms | title=Namma Pride March: Rainbow spread cheer, but with a dash of black | date=25 November 2019 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Iyer, Swathy R | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191129065826/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/namma-pride-march-rainbow-spreads-cheer-but-with-a-dash-of-black/articleshow/72216384.cms | archive-date=29 November 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/delhi-marched-against-trans-bill-2019-on-pride-day-779641.html | title=Delhi marched against Trans Bill 2019 on Pride Day | date=25 November 2019 | agency=Deccan Herald | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Banerjee, Rohini | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123135718/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/delhi-marched-against-trans-bill-2019-on-pride-day-779641.html | archive-date=23 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"jaya\">{{Cite news |last=Pathak |first=Sushmita |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/12/04/784398783/india-just-passed-a-trans-rights-bill-why-are-trans-activists-protesting-it |title=India Just Passed A Trans Rights Bill. Why Are Trans Activists Protesting It? |date=4 December 2019 |work=National Public Radio |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303211742/https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/12/04/784398783/india-just-passed-a-trans-rights-bill-why-are-trans-activists-protesting-it |archive-date=3 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The legislation also drew criticism from the [[All India Mahila Congress]] and opposition from parliamentarians including [[Jaya Bachchan]] and [[Sasmit Patra]], while [[Derek O\u2019Brien]] and Tiruchi Siva also expressed their concerns before the house.<ref name=\"jaya2\"/><ref name=\"jaya\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/a-bill-meant-to-protect-indias-transgender-community-instead-leaves-them-angry-and-aggrieved/2019/11/29/6c2c7b7e-116b-11ea-924c-b34d09bbc948_story.html | title=A bill meant to protect India\u2019s transgender community instead leaves them angry and aggrieved | date=30 November 2019 | agency=The Washington Post | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Masih, Niha | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302034520/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/a-bill-meant-to-protect-indias-transgender-community-instead-leaves-them-angry-and-aggrieved/2019/11/29/6c2c7b7e-116b-11ea-924c-b34d09bbc948_story.html | archive-date=2 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> After the legislation was passed by the parliament, transgender persons and activists protested against the legislation, organised meetings to address the situation, and urged the president not to sign and assent to the bill.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/mumbai/other/protests-held-in-dadar-against-transgender-persons-bill-2019/articleshow/72309119.cms | title=Protests held in Dadar against Transgender Persons Bill 2019 | work=Mumbai Mirror | date=1 December 2019 | accessdate=17 April 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191201051151/https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/mumbai/other/protests-held-in-dadar-against-transgender-persons-bill-2019/articleshow/72309119.cms | archive-date=1 December 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"jaya\"/> <ref>{{Cite news |last=Khan |first=Fatima |url=https://theprint.in/india/murder-of-gender-justice-activists-urge-president-kovind-not-to-sign-transgender-bill/327360/ |title=\u2018Murder of gender justice\u2019 \u2014 activists urge President Kovind not to sign transgender bill |date=27 November 2019 |work=The Print |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191201121026/https://theprint.in/india/murder-of-gender-justice-activists-urge-president-kovind-not-to-sign-transgender-bill/327360/ |archive-date=1 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> There were also protests by the queer community against the act as part of the [[Queer Azaadi Mumbai|Mumbai pride parade]], in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/take-back-trans-act-mumbai-trans-community/1726557 | title=Take back Trans Act: Mumbai Trans community | work=Outlook | date=5 February 2020 | agency=IANS | accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/mumbai-pride-2020-thousands-stand-in-solidarity-with-queer-muslims-amid-caa-nrc-chaos-urge-govt-to-amend-draconian-transgender-act-7991111.html | title=Mumbai Pride 2020: Thousands stand in solidarity with queer Muslims amid CAA-NRC chaos, urge govt to amend 'draconian' Transgender Act | work=Firstpost | date=25 February 2020 | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Manral, Avnisha | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315122340/https://www.firstpost.com/india/mumbai-pride-2020-thousands-stand-in-solidarity-with-queer-muslims-amid-caa-nrc-chaos-urge-govt-to-amend-draconian-transgender-act-7991111.html | archive-date=15 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe legislation has been criticised by [[Human Rights Watch]] and the [[International Commission of Jurists]].<ref name=\"jurists\">{{Cite news |last=Sharma |first=Neetu Chandra |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-protection-of-rights-bill-2019-11574774522034.html |title=Rajya Sabha passes Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2019 |date=26 November 2019 |work=Live Mint |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128004011/https://www.livemint.com/news/india/rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-protection-of-rights-bill-2019-11574774522034.html |archive-date=28 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"hrw\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/07/23/india-transgender-bill-raises-rights-concerns | title=India: Transgender Bill Raises Rights Concerns | date=23 July 2019 | agency=Human Rights Watch | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New York | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730050854/https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/07/23/india-transgender-bill-raises-rights-concerns | archive-date=30 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> In the run-up to the 2019 general elections to the Lok Sabha, Indian National Congress had promised in its electoral manifesto to withdraw the 2018 bill and introduce a new one, in consultation with members of the queer community.<ref name = \"manifesto\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thestatesman.com/elections-2019/congress-releases-poll-manifesto-promises-jobs-benefits-farmers-niti-aayog-1502742568.html | title=Congress manifesto promises 34 lakh jobs, farmer welfare, says will scrap NITI Aayog | date=2 April 2019 | agency=The Statesman | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=SNS Web | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817134723/https://www.thestatesman.com/elections-2019/congress-releases-poll-manifesto-promises-jobs-benefits-farmers-niti-aayog-1502742568.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The Communist Party of India (Marxist) had supported the passing of the 2014 bill in its electoral manifesto.<ref name = \"manifesto\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/elections/lok-sabha-2019/the-invisible-third-gender-voters/article26764806.ece | title=The invisible \u2018third gender\u2019 voters | date=8 April 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Rosario, Kennith | location=Mumbai}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 January 2020, the Supreme Court issued a notice to the central government in a petition filed by advocate and transgender rights activist, Swati Bidhan Baruah, challenging the constitutionality of the 2019 legislation.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/supreme-court-notice-to-centre-on-plea-against-transgender-act/story-HfBrPZBTFmusm9theecWoL.html | title=Supreme Court notice to Centre on plea against transgender act | work=Hindustan Times | date=28 January 2020 | accessdate=17 April 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129045020/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/supreme-court-notice-to-centre-on-plea-against-transgender-act/story-HfBrPZBTFmusm9theecWoL.html | archive-date=29 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/supreme-court-notice-to-centre-on-plea-against-transgender-act-2019-798774.html | title=Supreme Court notice to Centre on plea against Transgender Act, 2019| work=Deccan Herald | date=27 January 2020 | agency=Tripathi, Ashish | accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[LGBT rights in India]]\n*[[Human rights in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019}}\n* [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Expert_Committee_Report_%282014%29_1.pdf   Report of the Expert Committee on Issues Relating to Transgender Persons (27 January 2014)]\n* [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Transgender_Bill%2C_2015_-_PMB_passed_in_RS_2.pdf   The Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014]\n* [http://socialjustice.nic.in/writereaddata/UploadFile/TG%20bill%20gazette.pdf The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019]\n* [http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2020/215301.pdf  Notification dated 10 January 2020 commencing the provisions of the act]\n\n{{Indian legislation}}\n{{LGBT in India}}\n{{Transgender topics}}\n\n[[Category:LGBT rights in India]]\n[[Category:Modi administration]]\n[[Category:Transgender law]]\n[[Category:2019 in Indian law]]\n", "name_user": "Tamravidhir", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory and background:added full stop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transgender_Persons_(Protection_of_Rights)_Act,_2019"}
{"title_page": "Top Gun", "text_new": "{{About|the film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Top Gun\n| image          = Top Gun Movie.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Tony Scott]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Don Simpson]]\n* [[Jerry Bruckheimer]]\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jim Cash]]\n* [[Jack Epps Jr.]]\n}}\n| based on       = {{based on|''\"Top Guns\"''|Ehud Yonay}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Tom Cruise]]\n* [[Kelly McGillis]]\n* [[Val Kilmer]]\n* [[Anthony Edwards]]\n* [[Tom Skerritt]]}}<!--NAMES ON POSTER ONLY-->\n| music          = [[Harold Faltermeyer]]\n| cinematography = [[Jeffrey L. Kimball]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Chris Lebenzon]]\n* [[Billy Weber]]\n}}\n| studio         = [[Don Simpson]]/[[Jerry Bruckheimer|Jerry Bruckheimer Films]]\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1986|5|12|New York City|1986|5|16|United States}}<ref name=BOM>{{Mojo title|id=topgun}}</ref>\n| runtime        = 110 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $15 million and 35 million (2020)\n| gross          = $356.8 million<ref name=BOM/> and 837 million (2020)\nRentals\n$79,400,000 (USA)\n\n}}\n\n'''''Top Gun''''' is a 1986 American [[action drama film]] directed by [[Tony Scott]], and produced by [[Don Simpson]] and [[Jerry Bruckheimer]], in association with [[Paramount Pictures]]. The screenplay was written by [[Jim Cash]] and [[Jack Epps Jr.]], and was inspired by an article titled \"Top Guns\" published in ''[[California (magazine)|California]]'' magazine three years earlier. The film stars [[Tom Cruise]], [[Kelly McGillis]], [[Val Kilmer]], [[Anthony Edwards]], and [[Tom Skerritt]]. It also marked the debut of actor [[Adrian Pasdar]]. Cruise plays [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]] Pete \"Maverick\" Mitchell, a young [[naval aviator]] aboard the [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Enterprise|CVN-65|6}}. He and his [[Radar Intercept Officer]], Nick \"Goose\" Bradshaw (Edwards) are given the chance to train at the US Navy's [[United States Navy Strike Fighter Tactics Instructor program|Fighter Weapons School]] at [[Marine Corps Air Station Miramar#Naval Air Station|Naval Air Station Miramar]] in [[San Diego]], [[California]].\n\n''Top Gun'' was released on May 16, 1986. Upon its release, the film received generally mixed reviews from film critics but many particularly praised the action sequences, the effects, the aerial stunts, and the acting performances with Cruise and McGillis receiving the most praise. Four weeks after release, the number of theaters showing it increased by 45 percent.<ref name=bomweekly>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekly&id=topgun.htm |title=Top Gun Weekly |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=boxofficemojo.com |access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref> Despite its initial mixed critical reaction, the film was a huge commercial hit grossing [[US$]]356 million against a production budget of only US$15 million. The film maintained its popularity over the years and earned an [[IMAX]] 3D re-release in 2013. Additionally, the film won an [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] for \"[[Take My Breath Away]]\" performed by [[Berlin (band)|Berlin]].\n\nIn 2015, the United States [[Library of Congress]] selected the film for preservation in the [[National Film Registry]], finding it \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ghostbusters-top-gun-enter-national-849092|title='Ghostbusters,' 'Top Gun,' 'Shawshank' Enter National Film Registry|author=Mike Barnes|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 16, 2015|accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref> A sequel, titled ''[[Top Gun: Maverick]]'' is scheduled for release on December 23, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=D'Alessandro |first1=Anthony |title=\u2018Top Gun Maverick\u2019 Flies To Christmas Corridor, \u2018SpongeBob\u2019 Eyes Late Summer, \u2018Quiet Place II\u2019 To Debut Labor Day |url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/top-gun-maverick-flies-to-christmas-corridor-spongebob-eyes-late-summer-quiet-place-ii-to-debut-labor-day-1202898738/ |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=April 2, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- NOTE: According to WP:FILMPLOT guidelines, plot summaries for featured film articles should be 400-700 words. -->\n\n[[United States Naval Aviator]] [[Lieutenant (navy)|LT]] Pete \"Maverick\" Mitchell and his [[Radar Intercept Officer]] [[Lieutenant (junior grade)|LTJG]] Nick \"Goose\" Bradshaw fly the [[Grumman F-14 Tomcat|F-14A Tomcat]] aboard {{USS|Enterprise|CVN-65|6}}. During an interception with two hostile MiG-28 aircraft (portrayed by a [[Northrop F-5]]), Maverick gets missile lock on one, while the other hostile aircraft locks onto Maverick's wingman, Cougar. While Maverick drives off the remaining MiG-28, Cougar is too shaken to land, and Maverick, defying orders, shepherds him back to the carrier. Cougar gives up his [[Wings of Gold|wings]], citing his newborn child that he has never seen. Despite his dislike for Maverick's recklessness, [[Commander, Air Group|CAG]] \"Stinger\" sends him and Goose to attend Topgun{{sic}},<ref>https://www.fighterpilotpodcast.com/podcast/007-topgun-vs-top-gun/</ref> the Naval Fighter Weapons School at [[Naval Air Station Miramar]].\n\nAt a bar the day before Topgun starts, Maverick, assisted by Goose, unsuccessfully approaches a woman. Maverick learns the next day that she is Charlotte \"Charlie\" Blackwood, an [[Astrophysics|astrophysicist]] and civilian Topgun instructor. Charlie later becomes interested in Maverick upon learning of his inverted maneuver with the MiG-28, which disproves US intelligence on the enemy aircraft's performance.\n\nDuring Maverick's first training sortie he defeats instructor LCDR Rick \"Jester\" Heatherly but through reckless flying breaks two [[rules of engagement]] and is reprimanded by chief instructor CDR Mike \"Viper\" Metcalf. Privately, Jester confides that he admires Maverick's skill, but wouldn't trust him as a teammate in combat. Maverick also becomes a rival to top student LT Tom \"Iceman\" Kazansky, who considers Maverick's attitude \"dangerous\"\u2014as Maverick's tendency to abandon his team and pursue reckless objectives makes him \"unsafe\" to fly with. In class, Charlie also objects to Maverick's aggressive tactics but privately admits to him that she admires his flying and omitted it from her reports to hide her feelings for him, and the two begin a romantic relationship.\n\nDuring a training sortie, Maverick abandons his wingman \"Hollywood\" to chase Viper, who is impressed with his flying abilities but is defeated when Viper maneuvers Maverick into a position from which his wingman Jester can shoot down Maverick from behind, demonstrating the value of teamwork over individual prowess. Jester publicly tells Maverick that his flying is excellent, but that he should \"never leave [his] wingman.\"\n\nMaverick and Iceman, now direct competitors for the Topgun Trophy, chase an [[Douglas A-4 Skyhawk|A-4]] in a later training engagement. Maverick pressures Iceman to break off his engagement so he can shoot it down, but Maverick's F-14 flies through the [[Wake turbulence|jet wash]] of Iceman's aircraft and suffers a [[flameout]] of both engines, going into an unrecoverable [[spin (flight)|flat spin]].  Maverick and Goose [[ejection seat|eject]], but Goose hits the jettisoned [[aircraft canopy]] head-first and is killed.\n\nAlthough the board of inquiry clears Maverick of responsibility for Goose's death, he is overcome by guilt and his flying skill diminishes. Charlie and others attempt to console him, but Maverick considers retiring. He seeks advice from Viper, who reveals that he served with Maverick's father Duke Mitchell on {{USS|Oriskany|CV-34|6}} and was in the air battle in which Mitchell was killed. Contrary to official reports which faulted Mitchell, Viper reveals classified information that proves Mitchell died heroically and informs Maverick that he can succeed if he can regain his self-confidence. Maverick chooses to graduate, though Iceman wins the Top Gun Trophy.\n\nDuring the graduation party, Viper calls in the newly graduated aviators with the orders to deploy. Iceman, Hollywood, and Maverick are ordered to immediately return to ''Enterprise'' to deal with a \"crisis situation\", providing air support for the rescue of a stricken ship that has drifted into hostile waters.\n\nMaverick and Merlin (Cougar's former RIO) are assigned as back-up for F-14s flown by Iceman and Hollywood, despite Iceman's reservations over Maverick's state of mind. The subsequent hostile engagement with six MiGs sees Hollywood shot down; Maverick is scrambled alone due to a [[aircraft catapult|catapult]] failure and nearly retreats after encountering circumstances similar to those that caused Goose's death. Upon finally rejoining Iceman, the two are still badly outnumbered, but Maverick vocally refuses to leave Iceman without a wingman and manages to shoot down three MiGs. Iceman, shifting to offense also shoots one down, which forces the other two to flee. Upon their triumphant return to ''Enterprise'', Iceman and Maverick share newfound respect in each other, and Maverick throws Goose's dog tags overboard.\n\nOffered any assignment he chooses, Maverick decides to return to Topgun as an instructor. At a bar in Miramar, Maverick and Charlie reunite.\n\n== Cast ==\n<!-- opening credits title card billing -->\n* [[Tom Cruise]] as LT Pete \"Maverick\" Mitchell\n* [[Kelly McGillis]] as Charlotte \"Charlie\" Blackwood. The character is based on a real-life person, [[Christine Fox]], who worked at the [[Marine Corps Air Station Miramar]].<ref name=Richman1985>{{cite news|last=Richman|first=Alan|title=Air Warfare Expert Christine Fox\u2014Fighter Pilots Call Her \"Legs\"\u2014Inspires the New Movie Top Gun|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20091443,00.html|accessdate=December 22, 2013|newspaper=People Magazine|date=August 5, 1985|page=115}}</ref>\n* [[Val Kilmer]] as LT Tom \"Iceman\" Kazansky\n* [[Anthony Edwards]] as [[Lieutenant (junior grade)|LTJG]] Nick \"Goose\" Bradshaw\n* [[Tom Skerritt]] as [[Commander (United States)|CDR]] Mike \"Viper\" Metcalf\n<!-- 3 at a time -->\n* [[Michael Ironside]] as [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|LCDR]] Rick \"Jester\" Heatherly\n* [[John Stockwell (actor)|John Stockwell]] as LT Bill \"Cougar\" Cortell\n* [[Barry Tubb]] as LTJG Henry \"Wolfman\" Ruth\n* [[Rick Rossovich]] as LTJG Ron \"Slider\" Kerner\n* [[Tim Robbins]] as LTJG Sam \"Merlin\" Wells\n* [[Clarence Gilyard]] as LTJG Marcus \"Sundown\" Williams\n<!-- co-starring, 3 at a time -->\n* [[Whip Hubley]] as LT Rick \"Hollywood\" Neven\n* [[James Tolkan]] as CDR Tom \"Stinger\" Jardian\n* [[Meg Ryan]] as Carole Bradshaw\n<!-- opening credits billing ends here -->\n* [[Adrian Pasdar]] as LT Charles \"Chipper\" Piper\n\n== Production ==\n=== Background ===\nThe primary inspiration for the film was the article \"Top Guns\" by Ehud Yonay, from the May 1983 issue of ''[[California (magazine)|California]]'' magazine, which featured aerial photography by then-Lieutenant Commander Charles \"Heater\" Heatley.<ref name=\"Top Gun Movie -The 80s Rewind\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fast-rewind.com/topgun.htm|title=Top Gun|work=fast-rewind.com}}</ref> The article detailed the life of fighter pilots at Naval Air Station Miramar in [[San Diego]], self-nicknamed as \"Fightertown USA\". Numerous screenwriters allegedly turned down the project.<ref name=\"Top Gun Movie -The 80s Rewind\" /> Bruckheimer and Simpson went on to hire Jim Cash and Jack Epps, Jr., to write the first draft. The research methods, by Epps, included attendance at several declassified Topgun classes at Miramar and gaining experience by being flown in an F-14. The first draft failed to impress Bruckheimer and Simpson, and is considered to be very different from the final product in numerous ways.<ref>Special Edition DVD, Interview with Jack Epps</ref> Tony Scott was hired to direct on the strength of a commercial he had done for Swedish automaker [[Saab automobile|Saab]] in the early 1980s, where a [[Saab 900]] turbo is shown racing a [[Saab 37 Viggen]] fighter jet.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jets, jeans and Hovis|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2007/aug/24/1|newspaper=The Guardian|date=12 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nActor [[Matthew Modine]] turned down the role of [[Pete Mitchell (Top Gun)|LT Pete \"Maverick\" Mitchell]] (that went to Tom Cruise) because he felt the film's pro-military stance went against his politics. The character of Chipper Piper was created just for Pasdar as Scott loved his performance.<ref>https://www.phillymag.com/news/2007/06/19/exit-interview-adrian-pasdar/%3Famp%3D1&ved=2ahUKEwiFt9y_2LPkAhWGd98KHX1fDj04ChAWMAJ6BAgIEAE&usg=AOvVaw0BwMNNZVyZdJT2v7LgFHlg</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://nymag.com/news/intelligencer/encounter/57174/|title=154 Minutes With Matthew Modine|date=June 15\u201322, 2009|last=Murphy|first=Tim|magazine=New York magazine}}</ref>\n\nThe producers wanted the assistance of the US Navy in the production of the film. The Navy was influential in relation to script approval, which resulted in changes being made. The opening dogfight was moved to international waters as opposed to [[Cuba]], the language was toned down, and a scene that involved a crash on the deck of an aircraft carrier was also scrapped.<ref>Special Edition DVD, Interview with the producers</ref> Maverick's love interest was also changed from a female enlisted member of the Navy to a civilian contractor with the Navy, due to the US military's prohibition of fraternization between officers and enlisted personnel.<ref name=\"Top Gun Movie -The 80s Rewind\" /> The \"Charlie\" character also replaced an aerobics instructor from an early draft as a love interest for Maverick after producers were introduced to [[Christine Fox|Christine \"Legs\" Fox]], a civilian mathematician employed by the [[Center for Naval Analyses]] as a specialist in Maritime Air Superiority (MAS), developing tactics for aircraft carrier defense.<ref name=Richman1985/>\n\n[[Julianne Phillips]] was in consideration for the role of Charlie, and had been scheduled to perform a screen test opposite Tom Cruise.<ref name=AFI/>\n\nRear Admiral Pete \"Viper\" Pettigrew, a former Navy aviator, Vietnam War veteran, and Topgun instructor served as a technical advisor on the film, and also made a cameo appearance in the film as a colleague of Charlie's.\n\nFormer Top Gun instructor pilot and Congressman [[Duke Cunningham|Randy \"Duke\" Cunningham]] claimed to have been the inspiration for Pete Mitchell, although the film's producers have denied that the character was based on any specific Naval Aviator.<ref>{{cite news| first=Alex| last=Roth| newspaper=The San Diego Union-Tribune| url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/politics/cunningham/20060115-9999-lz1n15legend.html| title= down Cunningham's legend| date=2006-01-15| page=A-1| accessdate=2006-02-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:VF-111 TOPGUN MOVIE.jpg|thumb|F-14A Tomcats of Fighter Squadrons [[VF-51]] \"Screaming Eagles\" and [[VF-111 (1956-95)|VF-111]] \"Sundowners\", and F-5E/F Tiger IIs of the Navy Fighter Weapons School]]\n\nThe Navy made several aircraft from F-14 fighter squadron [[VF-51]] \"Screaming Eagles\" (which Tom Skerritt mentions in the scene at his home) available for the film. Paramount paid as much as US$7,800 per hour (equivalent to ${{inflation|US|7800|1985|r=-2|fmt=c}} today) for fuel and other operating costs whenever aircraft were flown outside their normal duties. Shots of the aircraft carrier sequences were filmed aboard USS ''Enterprise'', showing aircraft from F-14 squadrons [[VF-114]] \"Aardvarks\" and [[VFA-213|VF-213]] \"Black Lions\".<ref>[http://www.topgunbio.com/ Baranek, Dave \"Bio\", \"Topgun Days\"], Skyhorse Publishing, 2010. {{ISBN|978-1-61608-005-1}}</ref> The majority of the carrier flight deck shots were of normal aircraft operations and the film crew had to take what they could get, save for the occasional flyby which the film crew would request. During filming, director Tony Scott wanted to shoot aircraft landing and taking off, back-lit by the sun. During one particular filming sequence, the ship's commanding officer changed the ship's course, thus changing the light. When Scott asked if they could continue on their previous course and speed, he was informed by the commander that it cost US$25,000 (equivalent to ${{inflation|US|25000|1985|r=-3|fmt=c}} today) to turn the ship, and to continue on course. Scott wrote the carrier's captain a US$25,000 check so that the ship could be turned and he could continue shooting for another five minutes.<ref>Special Edition DVD, Interview with Tony Scott and Pete Pettigrew</ref>\n\n[[File:Filming of Top Gun movie (01) 1985.jpg|thumb|upright=.75|Filming and [[clapperboard]] of ''Top Gun'' on July 5, 1985.]]\n\nMost of the sequences of the aircraft maneuvering over land were shot at [[Naval Air Station Fallon]], in [[Nevada]], using ground-mounted cameras. Air-to-air shots were filmed using a [[Learjet]], piloted by Astrovision inventor and legendary pilot [[Clay Lacy]]. His name is misspelled in the closing credits, as Clay Lacey. [[Grumman]], manufacturer of the F-14, was commissioned by Paramount Pictures to create camera pods to be placed upon the aircraft<ref>{{cite book |last=Rogers |first=Pauline |date=1998 |title=Contemporary Cinematographers on Their Art |url=https://archive.org/details/contemporarycine00roge |url-access=registration |publisher=CRC Press |page=[https://archive.org/details/contemporarycine00roge/page/222 222] |isbn=9781136045776 }}</ref> that could be pointed toward either the front or rear of the aircraft providing outside shots at high altitude.\n\nIn July 1985, [[Kansas City Barbeque]] served as a filming location for two scenes. The first scene features Goose and Maverick singing \"[[Great Balls of Fire]]\" while seated at the piano. The final scene, where \"[[You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin']]\" can be heard on the restaurant's jukebox, was also filmed at the restaurant. Both scenes were filmed consecutively. After release of the movie, the restaurant went on to collect a significant amount of memorabilia from the motion picture until a kitchen fire on June 26, 2008, destroyed much of the restaurant. Some memorabilia and props, including the original piano used in the film, survived the fire, and the restaurant re-opened in November 2008.\n\nRenowned aerobatic pilot [[Art Scholl]] was hired to do in-flight camera work for the film. The original script called for a [[Spin (flight)|flat spin]], which Scholl was to perform and capture on a camera on the aircraft. The aircraft was observed to spin through its recovery altitude, at which time Scholl radioed \"I have a problem... I have a real problem\". He was unable to recover from the spin and crashed his [[Pitts Special]] bi-plane into the [[Pacific Ocean]] off the Southern California coast near [[Carlsbad, California|Carlsbad]] on September 16, 1985. Neither Scholl's body nor his aircraft was recovered, leaving the official cause of the accident unknown.<ref>Ashurst, Sam (November 4, 2008). [http://www.totalfilm.com/features/hollywood-s-deadliest-stunts Hollywood's deadliest stunts]. ''[[Total Film]]''.</ref> ''Top Gun'' was dedicated to Scholl's memory.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mw95w0WFqA0&t=6m12s|title=Top Gun \u2013 Abspann (Sat 1, 1989)|date=April 23, 2008|work=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nThe film was shot in the [[Super 35]] format, as anamorphic lenses were too large to fit inside the cockpits of the fighter jets.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Burum |editor1-first=Stephen |date=2007 |title=American Cinematographer Manual, Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1cYYAQAAIAAJ&q=&#034;optics+allow+this+is+one+of+the+reasons&#034;&dq=&#034;optics+allow+this+is+one+of+the+reasons&#034;&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjf9rvMm63kAhWClp4KHZHtCwgQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg |publisher=ASC Press |page=40 |isbn=9780935578317}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n{{further|Top Gun (soundtrack)}}\nThe ''Top Gun'' soundtrack is one of the most popular soundtracks to date, reaching [[RIAA certification|9\u00d7 Platinum certification]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?artist=%22Top+Gun%22# |title=RIAA Searchable Gold and Platinum Database |accessdate=July 6, 2012}} (may have to press the Search button)</ref> and #1 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 200 albums chart for five nonconsecutive weeks in the summer and fall of 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/1986-08-02/billboard-200|title=Top 200 Albums \u2013 Billboard|work=Billboard}}</ref> [[Harold Faltermeyer]], who previously worked with both [[Jerry Bruckheimer]] and [[Don Simpson]] on ''[[Beverly Hills Cop]]'', was sent the script of ''Top Gun'' by Bruckheimer before filming began. [[Giorgio Moroder]] and [[Tom Whitlock]] worked on numerous songs including the Oscar-winning \"[[Take My Breath Away]]\". [[Kenny Loggins]] performed two songs on the soundtrack, \"[[Playing with the Boys]]\", and \"[[Danger Zone (song)|Danger Zone]]\". [[Berlin (band)|Berlin]] recorded the song \"Take My Breath Away\", which would later win numerous awards, sending the band to international acclaim. After the release of Loggins's single \"Danger Zone\", sales of the album exploded, selling 7 million in the [[United States]] alone. On the re-release of the soundtrack in 2000, two songs that had been omitted from the original album (and had been released many years before the film was made), \"[[Great Balls of Fire]]\" by [[Jerry Lee Lewis]] and \"[[You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin']]\" by [[The Righteous Brothers]], were added. The soundtrack also includes \"[[Top Gun Anthem|''Top Gun'' Anthem]]\" and \"Memories\" by [[Steve Stevens]]/Faltermeyer and Faltermeyer.\n\nOther artists were considered for the soundtrack project but did not participate. [[Bryan Adams]] was considered as a potential candidate but refused to participate because he felt the film glorified war.<ref>{{URL|http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/21800%7C0/Top-Gun.html}}</ref> The band [[Toto (band)|Toto]] was originally meant to record \"Danger Zone\", and had also written and recorded a song \"Only You\" for the soundtrack. However, there was a dispute between Toto's lawyers and the producers of the film, paving the way for Loggins to record \"Danger Zone\" and \"Only You\" being omitted from the film entirely.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toto99.com/blog2010/index.php?/archives/785-TOP-GUN-soundtrack.html|title=toto99.com \u2013 Official TOTO Website \u2013 Encyclopedia|work=toto99.com}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n===Theatrical===\nThe film's premiere was held in New York City on May 12, 1986<ref name=premiere>{{cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/actor-tom-cruise-attends-the-top-gun-premiere-party-on-may-news-photo/156180769|title=Actor Tom Cruise attends the 'Top Gun' Premiere Party on May 12, 1986|accessdate=July 21, 2019|last=Gallela|first=Ron|via=[[Getty Images]]}}</ref> with another held in San Diego on May 15.<ref name=AFI>{{AFI film|id=57496}}</ref>\n\nThe film opened in the United States in 1,028 theaters on May 16, 1986.<ref name=BOM/>\n\n=== Home media ===\nIn addition to its box office success, ''Top Gun'' went on to break further records in the then still-developing home video market. It was the first new-release blockbuster on video cassette to be priced as low as $26.95 and, backed by a massive $8 million marketing campaign, including a ''Top Gun''-themed [[Diet Pepsi]] commercial,<ref>Taylor, Rod (March 1, 2005). [http://promomagazine.com/entertainmentmarketing/marketing_high_flyer/ High Flyer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060505151117/http://promomagazine.com/entertainmentmarketing/marketing_high_flyer/ |date=2006-05-05 }}. ''Promo''.</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ri5msDcS_DI&t=30 Opening to Top Gun 1987 VHS], tape print date: February 23, 1987 (posted to YouTube on March 5, 2016)</ref> the advance demand was such that the film became the best-selling videocassette in the industry's history on pre-orders alone, with over 1.9 million units ordered before its launch on March 10, 1987.<ref name=Takeoff>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|title='Top Gun' Cassettes In Record Takeoff: 1,900,000 Units|page=1|last=Bierbaum|first=Tom|date=March 4, 1987}}</ref> It eventually sold a record 2.9 million units.<ref name=\"price\">{{cite news |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DE0D9133FF934A25756C0A96E948260 |title=Wearing Spielberg Down To Put 'E.T.' on Cassette |author=Harmetz, Aljean |date=May 17, 1988}}</ref>\n\nThe film was first released in the U.S. on DVD under Paramount Pictures on October 21, 1998 and included the film in both Widescreen (non-anamorphic [[Univisium]] 2.00:1) and Full Screen ([[open matte]]) versions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/dvd/Top-Gun-DVD/2639/|title= Top Gun DVD|website=Blu-ray.com|date=October 21, 1998|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> ''Top Gun''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s home video success was again reflected by strong DVD sales, which were furthered by a Special Collector's Edition 2-disc DVD release in December 2004 in both Widescreen (anamorphic 2.39:1) and Full Screen (open matte) versions, that include new bonus features. Special features comprise [[audio commentary]] by Bruckheimer, Tony Scott and naval experts, four [[music video]]s including the \"Top Gun Anthem\" and \"Take My Breath Away\", a six-part documentary on the making of ''Top Gun'', and vintage gallery with interviews, behind-the-scenes and survival training [[featurette]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/dvd/Top-Gun-DVD/6547/|title= Top Gun DVD Widescreen Special Collector\u2019s Edition|website=Blu-ray.com|date=December 14, 2004|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, the film was first released on [[Blu-ray]] disc on July 29, 2008 with the same supplemental features as the Collector's Edition DVD and also as a 2-disc limited edition [[3-D film|3D]] copy on February 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Top-Gun-Blu-ray/475/|title= Top Gun Blu-ray|website=Blu-ray.com|date=July 29, 2008|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Top-Gun-3D-Blu-ray/60004/|title=Top Gun Limited 3D Edition / Blu-ray 3D + Blu-ray|publisher=Blu-ray.com|date=February 19, 2013|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> The remastered Blu-ray and Digital Copy version of the film was released on May 19, 2019 on [https://www.paramountmovies.com/movies/top-gun Paramount Movies].\n''Top Gun'' is scheduled to be released in the U.S. on remastered Blu-ray and 4K [[Ultra HD]] on May 19, 2020 with two new special features titled The Legacy of ''Top Gun'' and On Your Six: Thirty years of ''Top Gun'', with the remaining bonus features being ported over.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Top-Gun-Blu-ray/266605/|title=Top Gun Blu-ray + Digital|website=Blu-ray.com|date=May 19, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=26592|title=Top Gun 4K Blu-ray|publisher=Blu-ray.com|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== IMAX 3D re-release ===\n''Top Gun'' was re-released in IMAX 3D on February 8, 2013, for six days.<ref name=\"Slash Film\">{{cite news |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/top-gun-gets-imax-3d-re-release-in-february/ |title=''Top Gun'' Gets IMAX Re-Release in February |author=Lussier, Germain |publisher=Flash Film |date=2012-12-11 |accessdate=2012-12-11}}</ref> A four-minute preview of the conversion, featuring the \"Danger Zone\" flight sequence, was screened at the 2012 [[International Broadcasting Convention]] in [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]].<ref name=\"Hollywood Reporter\">{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/top-gun-coming-theaters-3d-234032 |title=''Top Gun'' Coming to Theaters in 3D |author=Giardina, Carolyn |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=2011-09-12 |accessdate=2011-09-14}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Box office ===\nThe film quickly became a success and was the highest-grossing film of 1986. It would be six months before its theater count dropped below that of its opening week.<ref name=bomweekly /> It was number one on its first weekend with a gross of US$8,193,052,<ref name=BOM/> and went on to a total domestic gross of US$176,781,728.<ref name=BOM/> Internationally it took in an estimated US$177,030,000<ref name=BOM/> for a worldwide box office total of US$353,811,728.<ref name=BOM/> The film sold an estimated 47,650,100 tickets in North America in its initial theatrical run.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=July 13, 2016|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=topgun.htm&adjust_yr=1&p=.htm|title=Top Gun (1986)|website=Box Office Mojo}}</ref>\n\nThe film grossed an additional US$3,018,873 in its IMAX re-release in 2013 bringing its domestic gross to US$179,800,601 and its worldwide gross to US$356,830,601.<ref name=BOM/>\n\n=== Critical response ===\nUpon the film's original release, critical response was mixed. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 55% based on reviews from 55 critics, with an average rating of 5.85/10. The website's critical consensus states: \"Though it features some of the most memorable and electrifying aerial footage shot with an expert eye for action, ''Top Gun'' offers too little for non-adolescent viewers to chew on when its characters aren't in the air.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/top_gun |title=Top Gun (1986) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 50 out of 100 based on 15 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/top-gun |title=Top Gun Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade A on scale of A to F.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |work= [[CinemaScore]] |url-status=live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 2018-12-20 }}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film 2.5 out of 4 stars, saying that \"Movies like ''Top Gun'' are hard to review because the good parts are so good and the bad parts are so relentless. The dogfights are absolutely the best since [[Clint Eastwood]]'s electrifying aerial scenes in [[Firefox (film)|''Firefox'']]. But look out for the scenes where the people talk to one another.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/top-gun-1986|title=Top Gun|author=Roger Ebert|work=Roger Ebert.com|date=May 16, 1986|accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\nThe film was nominated for and won many awards, most prominently for its sound and effects. The film won the following awards:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category \n! Recipients\n|-\n| 1987\n| ASCAP Film and Television Music Awards\n| Most Performed Songs from Motion Pictures \n| Giorgio Moroder and Tom Whitlock for the song \"[[Take My Breath Away]]\".\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[Academy Award]]s\n| Best Original Song \n| Giorgio Moroder (music) and Tom Whitlock (lyrics) for \"Take My Breath Away\".\n|-\n| 1986\n| Apex Scroll Awards\n| Achievement in Sound Effects\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[Brit Awards|BRIT Awards]]\n| Best Soundtrack\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[Golden Globe Award]]s\n| Best Original Song \u2013 Motion Picture \n| Giorgio Moroder (music) and Tom Whitlock (lyrics) for the song \"Take My Breath Away\".\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[Goldene Leinwand|Golden Screen Award]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[Grammy Award]]s\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Instrumental Performance|Best Pop Instrumental Performance (Orchestra, Group or Soloist)]] \n| Harold Faltermeyer and [[Steve Stevens]] for \"[[Top Gun Anthem|''Top Gun'' Anthem]]\".\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1987\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Motion Picture Sound Editors]]\n| Golden Reel Award for Best Sound Editing\n|\n|-\n| Best Sound Editing \u2013 Sound Effects\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[People's Choice Award]]s\n| Favorite Motion Picture\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| Award of the Japanese Academy\n| Best Foreign Language Film\n|\n|}\n\nThe film was nominated for the following awards:\n\n* Academy Awards (1987)<ref name=\"Oscars1987\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1987 |title=The 59th Academy Awards (1987) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=2011-10-16|work=oscars.org}}</ref>\n** Best Sound Effects Editing \u2013 [[Cecelia Hall]] and [[George Watters II]]\n** Best Film Editing \u2013 [[Billy Weber]] and [[Chris Lebenzon]]\n** Best Sound \u2013 [[Donald O. Mitchell]], [[Kevin O'Connell (sound mixer)|Kevin O'Connell]], [[Rick Kline]] and [[William B. Kaplan]]\n** Best Original Song \u2013 Giorgio Moroder and Tom Whitlock for \"Take My Breath Away\"\n* Apex Scroll Awards (1986)\n** Actress in a Supporting Role \u2013 Meg Ryan\n** Film Editing \u2013 Billy Weber and Chris Lebenzon\n** Best Original Song \u2013 Motion Picture \u2013 Giorgio Moroder (music) and Tom Whitlock (lyrics) for the song \"Take My Breath Away\".\n** Best Picture \u2013 [[Don Simpson]], [[Jerry Bruckheimer]]\n** Achievement in Compilation Soundtrack\n** Achievement in Sound\n* Golden Globe Awards (1987)\n** Best Original Score \u2013 Motion Picture \u2013 Harold Faltermeyer\n* Award of the Japanese Academy (1988)\n** Best Foreign Language Film\n* Fennecus Awards (1986)\n** Achievement in Compilation Soundtrack\n** Best Original Song \u2013 Motion Picture \u2013 Giorgio Moroder (music) and Tom Whitlock (lyrics) for the song \"Take My Breath Away\".\n** Film Editing \u2013 Billy Weber and Chris Lebenzon\n** Achievement in Sound\n** Achievement in Sound Effects\n\nIn 2008, the film was ranked at number 455 in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s list of the 500 greatest films of all time.<ref>[https://www.empireonline.com/500/8.asp The 500 Greatest Movies of All Time]. ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''.</ref> [[Yahoo! Movies]] ranked ''Top Gun'' #19 on their list of greatest action films of all-time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/|title=Yahoo Movies|work=yahoo.com}}</ref> The film was nominated multiple times for various AFI lists, but broke through only once. In 2005, the line \"I feel the need... the need for speed!\" was ranked 94 on [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes]] list.\n\n;[[American Film Institute]] list\n*[[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes]]:\n**\"I feel the need \u2014 the need for speed.\" \u2013 #94\n\n=== Effect on military recruiting ===\nMovie producer [[John Davis (producer)|John Davis]] said that ''Top Gun'' was a recruiting video for the Navy, that people saw the movie and said, \"Wow! I want to be a pilot.\" The Navy had recruitment booths in some theaters to attract enthusiastic patrons.<ref>[http://film.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/Guardian/0,4029,543821,00.html Top Gun versus Sergeant Bilko? No contest, says the Pentagon]. ''[[The Guardian]]''. August 29, 2001.</ref> After the film's release, the US Navy stated that the number of young men who joined wanting to be Naval Aviators went up by 500 percent.<ref>{{cite book|last=Robb|first=David|title=Operation Hollywood: How the Pentagon Shapes and Censors the Movies|publisher=Prometheus Books|location=New York|year=2004|pages=[https://archive.org/details/operationhollywo00robb/page/180 180\u2013182]|isbn=1-59102-182-0|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/operationhollywo00robb/page/180}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign affairs===\nOn January 23, 2011, China's state broadcaster ''[[China Central Television]]'' published a TV news story about the alleged efficiency of Chinese fighter pilots which incorporated footage from the ''Top Gun'' action sequences. Chinese internet users noticed the plagiarism, whereupon the broadcast was immediately withdrawn. Ironically, this occurred shortly after the initiation of a Chinese campaign to purge such forged reports; CCTV has declined comments on this incident.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://blogs.wsj.com/chinarealtime/2011/01/28/video-cctv-tries-to-pass-off-%E2%80%98top-gun%E2%80%99-clip-as-military-drill/ |title = Video: CCTV Tries to Pass Off \u2018Top Gun\u2019 Clip as Military Drill? |newspaper = [[The Wall Street Journal]] |last = Chin |first = Josh |date = January 28, 2011|accessdate=2018-08-20}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n{{in popular culture|section|date=July 2019}} \n[[Bomber jacket]] sales increased and [[Ray-Ban Aviator]] [[sunglasses]] jumped 40%, due to their use by characters in the film.<ref name=\"rayban\">{{cite news | work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | title=Through A Glass Darkly | url=http://www.time.com/time/archive/preview/0,10987,991503,00.html |author1=August, Melissa |author2=Derrow, Michelle |author3=Durham, Aisha |author4=Levy, Daniel S. |author5=Lofaro, Lina |author6=Spitz, David |author7=Taylor, Chris | date=July 12, 1999 |accessdate=November 8, 2006}}</ref>\n\nSince its initial release, the film has made many top film lists and has been the subject of comedic interpretation.\n\nThe 1991 film ''[[Hot Shots!]]'' was a comedy spoof of ''Top Gun''.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1991/07/31/movies/review-film-pilots-in-hot-shots-shoot-down-top-gun-in-a-hail-of-parody.html Review/Film; Pilots in 'Hot Shots!' Shoot Down 'Top Gun' In a Hail of Parody-NY Times]</ref>\n\nThe masculine theme of the film has been the subject of humorous examination, with the [[Homoeroticism|homoerotic]] subtext examined in a monologue performed by [[Quentin Tarantino]] in the 1994 film ''[[Sleep with Me]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Modleski|first1=Tania|author-link=Tania Modleski|title=Misogynist Films: Teaching Top Gun|journal=Cinema Journal|date=November 19, 2007|volume=47|issue=1|pages=102\u2013103|doi=10.1353/cj.2007.0056|issn=1527-2087}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=simmons/030904|title=ESPN.com: Page 2 : 'Talk to me, Goose. Talk to me.'|work=go.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://reelchange.net/2013/02/12/why-the-homoeroticism-in-top-gun-matters/|title=Why the Homoeroticism in \"Top Gun\" Matters|work=Reel Change|date=2013-02-12}}</ref><ref>http://www.cracked.com/funny-1906-quentin-tarantino-movies/ ''Cracked Magazine.com''\n\"Tarantino on Pop Culture (AKA If Cracked.com Was Written on Cocaine)\"</ref>\n\n''Top Gun'' is one of many war and action films, especially those by Jerry Bruckheimer, parodied in the 2004 comedy ''[[Team America: World Police]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2004/10/strings_attached.html|title=Strings Attached|journal=Slate|first=David|last=Edelstein|date=October 14, 2004}}</ref>\n\n''Top Gun'' along with ''[[A Few Good Men]]'' are recognized for being an inspiration for the TV series ''[[JAG (TV series)|JAG]]'' and for the [[NCIS (franchise)|''NCIS'' franchise]] in turn.  The entire JAG/NCIS franchise is also owned by Paramount.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Karlen|first1=Neal|title=COVER STORY;From the Man Behind 'Magnum, P.I.,' 'Top Gun' Meets 'A Few Good Men' By NEAL KARLEN|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/05/tv/cover-story-from-the-man-behind-magnum-pi-top-gun-meets-a-few-good-men.html|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=May 3, 2018|date=1995-11-05}}</ref>\n\nThe [[DisneyToon Studios]] film ''[[Planes (film)|Planes]]'' (2013), pays homage to ''Top Gun'' with Val Kilmer and Anthony Edwards appearing in the film as part of the voice cast.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywood.com/movies/disney-planes-top-gun-val-kilmer-anthony-edwards-57157487/ |title=Disney's 'Planes' Taps Val Kilmer and Anthony Edwards for 'Top Gun' Homage - PIC |last=Blauvelt  |first=Christian |date=2013-03-27 |website=hollywood.com |access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref>\n\nTwo Chinese films, 2011's ''Jian Shi Chu Ji'' (\"Skyfighters\") and 2017's ''Kong Tian Lie'' (\"[[Sky Hunter]]\"), were based on ''Top Gun''.<ref>{{cite news|author=Groffman, Nicolas|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2170552/top-gun-was-twice-remade-chinese-why-didnt-anybody-notice-clue|title=Top Gun was twice remade in Chinese, why didn't anybody notice? Clue: PLA|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=2018-10-29|accessdate=2018-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== Sequel ==\n{{main|Top Gun: Maverick}}\nA sequel has been in active development since at least 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2010/10/top_gun_2.html|title=''Top Gun 2'' is Heading to the Runway|last=Brodesser-Akner|first=Claude|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] magazine|date=October 13, 2010|accessdate=October 15, 2010}}</ref>  However plans were complicated by Scott's death in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/blogs/movie-talk/top-gun-producer-jerry-bruckheimer-reveals-won-over-233712961.html|title='Top Gun' producer Jerry Bruckheimer reveals how he won over Tom Cruise|work=Yahoo!|date=January 23, 2013|accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref> In 2013 Bruckheimer said, \"For 30 years we've been trying to make a sequel and we're not going to stop. We still want to do it with Tom and Paramount are still interested in making it. What Tom tells me is that no matter where he goes in the world, people refer to him as Maverick. It's something he is excited about so as long as he keeps his enthusiasm hopefully we'll get it made.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flickeringmyth.com/2013/06/jerry-bruckheimer-says-top-gun-2-is.html|title=Jerry Bruckheimer says Top Gun 2 is still on the cards|work=Flickering Myth|date=June 10, 2013|accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBy September 2014 it was revealed that Justin Marks was in negotiations to write the screenplay,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/top-gun-2-lands-jungle-731131|title='Top Gun 2' Lands 'Jungle Book' Writer (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 8, 2014|accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref> which was confirmed that following June.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/top-gun-2-maverick-drone-warfare-1201529697/| title='Top Gun 2\u2032 to Feature Maverick, Drone Warfare|last=Zumberge|first=Marianne|magazine=Variety|date=June 26, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015}}</ref> Marks would go on later to say that the film was a dream project for him, calling the original an \"iconic film in my memory\" due in part to it being one of the first films he remembers seeing in a movie theater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://creativescreenwriting.com/king-of-the-swingers-justin-marks-on-the-jungle-book/|title=King of the Swingers: Justin Marks on 'The Jungle Book'|first=Christopher|last=McKittrick|work=Creative Screenwriting|date=April 19, 2016|accessdate=September 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, during the promotional tour for ''[[The Mummy (2017 film)|The Mummy]]'', Cruise confirmed that a sequel to ''Top Gun'' will start filming in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/05/23/tom-cruise-top-gun-2-definitely-happening/|title=Tom Cruise Says 'Top Gun 2' Is 'Definitely Happening'|date=May 23, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> By June of the same year, he said that the title will be ''Top Gun: Maverick'' with Faltermeyer back as composer for the sequel. Cruise further stated that, \"Aviators are back, the need for speed. We're going to have big, fast machines. It's going to be a competition film, like the first one\u2026but a progression for Maverick.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/06/02/top-gun-2-title-tom-cruise-top-gun-maverick|title=In Which Tom Cruise Reveals The Title Of The TOP GUN Sequel|first=Scott|last=Wampler|date=June 2, 2017|website=Birth.Movies.Death.}}</ref> Later that month it was announced [[Joseph Kosinski]], who directed Cruise in 2013's ''[[Oblivion (2013 film)|Oblivion]]'', was set to direct the sequel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/top-gun-sequel-release-july-12-2019-tom-cruiise-joseph-kosinski-jerry-bruckheimer-paramount-1202123050/|title=Paramount Sets \u2018Top Gun 2\u2019 For July 2019; Joseph Kosinski Firmed For Tom Cruise Pic|work=Deadline Hollywood |date=June 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe release date has since been pushed back one year to June 2020, and later to December of that same year. A trailer was released for the first time at ComicCon International on July 18, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/news/ni62189853|title=\u2018Top Gun\u2019 Sequel Release Pushed Back One Year at Paramount|website=IMDb|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i6tDB7k9Ask</ref>\n\n== Video games ==\n{{Main|List of Top Gun video games}}\n''Top Gun'' also spawned a number of [[video game]]s for various platforms. The [[Top Gun (1986 video game)|original game]] was released in 1986 under the same title as the film. It was released on [[Commodore 64]], [[ZX Spectrum]], [[Amstrad CPC]], and [[Atari ST]]. Another game, also titled ''[[Top Gun (1987 video game)|Top Gun]]'', was released in 1987 for [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] (NES) and [[Nintendo VS. System]] arcade cabinets. In the 1987 game, the player pilots an F-14 Tomcat fighter, and has to complete four missions. A sequel, ''Top Gun: The Second Mission'', was released for the NES three years later.\n\nAnother game, ''[[Top Gun: Fire at Will]]'', was released in 1996 for the PC and later for the [[PlayStation|Sony PlayStation]] platform. ''[[Top Gun: Hornet's Nest]]'' was released in 1998. ''[[Top Gun: Combat Zones]]'' was released for [[PlayStation 2]] in 2001 and was subsequently released for the [[GameCube]] and [[Microsoft Windows]]. ''Combat Zones'' features other aircraft besides the F-14. In 2006, another game simply titled ''Top Gun'' was released for the [[Nintendo DS]]. A 2010 game, also titled ''[[Top Gun (2010 video game)|Top Gun]]'', retells the film's story. At E3 2011, a new game was announced, ''Top Gun: Hard Lock'', which was released in March 2012 for [[Xbox 360]], PC, and [[PlayStation 3]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Top Gun (film, 1986)}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{AFI film|id=57496}}\n* {{IMDb title|0092099}}\n* {{tcmdb title|16475}}\n* [http://www.fandango.com/movie-news/top-gun-30th-anniversary-remember-the-movie-with-this-exclusive-artwork-750546 'Top Gun' 30th Anniversary Exclusive Art Work] on [[Fandango (ticket service)|Fandango]]\n* {{Allmovie title|50435}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|top_gun}}\n* [https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=topgun.htm Top Gun] at [[Box Office Mojo]]\n* [https://www.paramountmovies.com/movies/top-gun Paramount Movies]\n{{Tony Scott}}\n{{Jerry Bruckheimer}}\n\n[[Category:1986 films]]\n[[Category:1980s action drama films]]\n[[Category:2013 3D films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American aviation films]]\n[[Category:American action drama films]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Original Song Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Cold War aviation films]]\n[[Category:Films about aviators]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on newspaper and magazine articles]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Don Simpson]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Tony Scott]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Jerry Bruckheimer]]\n[[Category:Films set in San Diego]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Films shot in San Diego]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films about the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:United States National Film Registry films]]\n[[Category:Top Gun]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Harold Faltermeyer]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Giorgio Moroder]]\n[[Category:3D re-releases]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Top Gun\n| image          = Top Gun Movie.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Tony Scott]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Don Simpson]]\n* [[Jerry Bruckheimer]]\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jim Cash]]\n* [[Jack Epps Jr.]]\n}}\n| based on       = {{based on|''\"Top Guns\"''|Ehud Yonay}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Tom Cruise]]\n* [[Kelly McGillis]]\n* [[Val Kilmer]]\n* [[Anthony Edwards]]\n* [[Tom Skerritt]]}}<!--NAMES ON POSTER ONLY-->\n| music          = [[Harold Faltermeyer]]\n| cinematography = [[Jeffrey L. Kimball]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Chris Lebenzon]]\n* [[Billy Weber]]\n}}\n| studio         = [[Don Simpson]]/[[Jerry Bruckheimer|Jerry Bruckheimer Films]]\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1986|5|12|New York City|1986|5|16|United States}}<ref name=BOM>{{Mojo title|id=topgun}}</ref>\n| runtime        = 110 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $15 million and 35 million (2020)\n| gross          = $356.8 million<ref name=BOM/> and 837 million (2020)\n}}\n\n'''''Top Gun''''' is a 1986 American [[action drama film]] directed by [[Tony Scott]], and produced by [[Don Simpson]] and [[Jerry Bruckheimer]], in association with [[Paramount Pictures]]. The screenplay was written by [[Jim Cash]] and [[Jack Epps Jr.]], and was inspired by an article titled \"Top Guns\" published in ''[[California (magazine)|California]]'' magazine three years earlier. The film stars [[Tom Cruise]], [[Kelly McGillis]], [[Val Kilmer]], [[Anthony Edwards]], and [[Tom Skerritt]]. It also marked the debut of actor [[Adrian Pasdar]]. Cruise plays [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]] Pete \"Maverick\" Mitchell, a young [[naval aviator]] aboard the [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Enterprise|CVN-65|6}}. He and his [[Radar Intercept Officer]], Nick \"Goose\" Bradshaw (Edwards) are given the chance to train at the US Navy's [[United States Navy Strike Fighter Tactics Instructor program|Fighter Weapons School]] at [[Marine Corps Air Station Miramar#Naval Air Station|Naval Air Station Miramar]] in [[San Diego]], [[California]].\n\n''Top Gun'' was released on May 16, 1986. Upon its release, the film received generally mixed reviews from film critics but many particularly praised the action sequences, the effects, the aerial stunts, and the acting performances with Cruise and McGillis receiving the most praise. Four weeks after release, the number of theaters showing it increased by 45 percent.<ref name=bomweekly>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekly&id=topgun.htm |title=Top Gun Weekly |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=boxofficemojo.com |access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref> Despite its initial mixed critical reaction, the film was a huge commercial hit grossing [[US$]]356 million against a production budget of only US$15 million. The film maintained its popularity over the years and earned an [[IMAX]] 3D re-release in 2013. Additionally, the film won an [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] for \"[[Take My Breath Away]]\" performed by [[Berlin (band)|Berlin]].\n\nIn 2015, the United States [[Library of Congress]] selected the film for preservation in the [[National Film Registry]], finding it \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ghostbusters-top-gun-enter-national-849092|title='Ghostbusters,' 'Top Gun,' 'Shawshank' Enter National Film Registry|author=Mike Barnes|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 16, 2015|accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref> A sequel, titled ''[[Top Gun: Maverick]]'' is scheduled for release on December 23, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=D'Alessandro |first1=Anthony |title=\u2018Top Gun Maverick\u2019 Flies To Christmas Corridor, \u2018SpongeBob\u2019 Eyes Late Summer, \u2018Quiet Place II\u2019 To Debut Labor Day |url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/top-gun-maverick-flies-to-christmas-corridor-spongebob-eyes-late-summer-quiet-place-ii-to-debut-labor-day-1202898738/ |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=April 2, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- NOTE: According to WP:FILMPLOT guidelines, plot summaries for featured film articles should be 400-700 words. -->\n\n[[United States Naval Aviator]] [[Lieutenant (navy)|LT]] Pete \"Maverick\" Mitchell and his [[Radar Intercept Officer]] [[Lieutenant (junior grade)|LTJG]] Nick \"Goose\" Bradshaw fly the [[Grumman F-14 Tomcat|F-14A Tomcat]] aboard {{USS|Enterprise|CVN-65|6}}. During an interception with two hostile MiG-28 aircraft (portrayed by a [[Northrop F-5]]), Maverick gets missile lock on one, while the other hostile aircraft locks onto Maverick's wingman, Cougar. While Maverick drives off the remaining MiG-28, Cougar is too shaken to land, and Maverick, defying orders, shepherds him back to the carrier. Cougar gives up his [[Wings of Gold|wings]], citing his newborn child that he has never seen. Despite his dislike for Maverick's recklessness, [[Commander, Air Group|CAG]] \"Stinger\" sends him and Goose to attend Topgun{{sic}},<ref>https://www.fighterpilotpodcast.com/podcast/007-topgun-vs-top-gun/</ref> the Naval Fighter Weapons School at [[Naval Air Station Miramar]].\n\nAt a bar the day before Topgun starts, Maverick, assisted by Goose, unsuccessfully approaches a woman. Maverick learns the next day that she is Charlotte \"Charlie\" Blackwood, an [[Astrophysics|astrophysicist]] and civilian Topgun instructor. Charlie later becomes interested in Maverick upon learning of his inverted maneuver with the MiG-28, which disproves US intelligence on the enemy aircraft's performance.\n\nDuring Maverick's first training sortie he defeats instructor LCDR Rick \"Jester\" Heatherly but through reckless flying breaks two [[rules of engagement]] and is reprimanded by chief instructor CDR Mike \"Viper\" Metcalf. Privately, Jester confides that he admires Maverick's skill, but wouldn't trust him as a teammate in combat. Maverick also becomes a rival to top student LT Tom \"Iceman\" Kazansky, who considers Maverick's attitude \"dangerous\"\u2014as Maverick's tendency to abandon his team and pursue reckless objectives makes him \"unsafe\" to fly with. In class, Charlie also objects to Maverick's aggressive tactics but privately admits to him that she admires his flying and omitted it from her reports to hide her feelings for him, and the two begin a romantic relationship.\n\nDuring a training sortie, Maverick abandons his wingman \"Hollywood\" to chase Viper, who is impressed with his flying abilities but is defeated when Viper maneuvers Maverick into a position from which his wingman Jester can shoot down Maverick from behind, demonstrating the value of teamwork over individual prowess. Jester publicly tells Maverick that his flying is excellent, but that he should \"never leave [his] wingman.\"\n\nMaverick and Iceman, now direct competitors for the Topgun Trophy, chase an [[Douglas A-4 Skyhawk|A-4]] in a later training engagement. Maverick pressures Iceman to break off his engagement so he can shoot it down, but Maverick's F-14 flies through the [[Wake turbulence|jet wash]] of Iceman's aircraft and suffers a [[flameout]] of both engines, going into an unrecoverable [[spin (flight)|flat spin]].  Maverick and Goose [[ejection seat|eject]], but Goose hits the jettisoned [[aircraft canopy]] head-first and is killed.\n\nAlthough the board of inquiry clears Maverick of responsibility for Goose's death, he is overcome by guilt and his flying skill diminishes. Charlie and others attempt to console him, but Maverick considers retiring. He seeks advice from Viper, who reveals that he served with Maverick's father Duke Mitchell on {{USS|Oriskany|CV-34|6}} and was in the air battle in which Mitchell was killed. Contrary to official reports which faulted Mitchell, Viper reveals classified information that proves Mitchell died heroically and informs Maverick that he can succeed if he can regain his self-confidence. Maverick chooses to graduate, though Iceman wins the Top Gun Trophy.\n\nDuring the graduation party, Viper calls in the newly graduated aviators with the orders to deploy. Iceman, Hollywood, and Maverick are ordered to immediately return to ''Enterprise'' to deal with a \"crisis situation\", providing air support for the rescue of a stricken ship that has drifted into hostile waters.\n\nMaverick and Merlin (Cougar's former RIO) are assigned as back-up for F-14s flown by Iceman and Hollywood, despite Iceman's reservations over Maverick's state of mind. The subsequent hostile engagement with six MiGs sees Hollywood shot down; Maverick is scrambled alone due to a [[aircraft catapult|catapult]] failure and nearly retreats after encountering circumstances similar to those that caused Goose's death. Upon finally rejoining Iceman, the two are still badly outnumbered, but Maverick vocally refuses to leave Iceman without a wingman and manages to shoot down three MiGs. Iceman, shifting to offense also shoots one down, which forces the other two to flee. Upon their triumphant return to ''Enterprise'', Iceman and Maverick share newfound respect in each other, and Maverick throws Goose's dog tags overboard.\n\nOffered any assignment he chooses, Maverick decides to return to Topgun as an instructor. At a bar in Miramar, Maverick and Charlie reunite.\n\n== Cast ==\n<!-- opening credits title card billing -->\n* [[Tom Cruise]] as LT Pete \"Maverick\" Mitchell\n* [[Kelly McGillis]] as Charlotte \"Charlie\" Blackwood. The character is based on a real-life person, [[Christine Fox]], who worked at the [[Marine Corps Air Station Miramar]].<ref name=Richman1985>{{cite news|last=Richman|first=Alan|title=Air Warfare Expert Christine Fox\u2014Fighter Pilots Call Her \"Legs\"\u2014Inspires the New Movie Top Gun|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20091443,00.html|accessdate=December 22, 2013|newspaper=People Magazine|date=August 5, 1985|page=115}}</ref>\n* [[Val Kilmer]] as LT Tom \"Iceman\" Kazansky\n* [[Anthony Edwards]] as [[Lieutenant (junior grade)|LTJG]] Nick \"Goose\" Bradshaw\n* [[Tom Skerritt]] as [[Commander (United States)|CDR]] Mike \"Viper\" Metcalf\n<!-- 3 at a time -->\n* [[Michael Ironside]] as [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|LCDR]] Rick \"Jester\" Heatherly\n* [[John Stockwell (actor)|John Stockwell]] as LT Bill \"Cougar\" Cortell\n* [[Barry Tubb]] as LTJG Henry \"Wolfman\" Ruth\n* [[Rick Rossovich]] as LTJG Ron \"Slider\" Kerner\n* [[Tim Robbins]] as LTJG Sam \"Merlin\" Wells\n* [[Clarence Gilyard]] as LTJG Marcus \"Sundown\" Williams\n<!-- co-starring, 3 at a time -->\n* [[Whip Hubley]] as LT Rick \"Hollywood\" Neven\n* [[James Tolkan]] as CDR Tom \"Stinger\" Jardian\n* [[Meg Ryan]] as Carole Bradshaw\n<!-- opening credits billing ends here -->\n* [[Adrian Pasdar]] as LT Charles \"Chipper\" Piper\n\n== Production ==\n=== Background ===\nThe primary inspiration for the film was the article \"Top Guns\" by Ehud Yonay, from the May 1983 issue of ''[[California (magazine)|California]]'' magazine, which featured aerial photography by then-Lieutenant Commander Charles \"Heater\" Heatley.<ref name=\"Top Gun Movie -The 80s Rewind\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fast-rewind.com/topgun.htm|title=Top Gun|work=fast-rewind.com}}</ref> The article detailed the life of fighter pilots at Naval Air Station Miramar in [[San Diego]], self-nicknamed as \"Fightertown USA\". Numerous screenwriters allegedly turned down the project.<ref name=\"Top Gun Movie -The 80s Rewind\" /> Bruckheimer and Simpson went on to hire Jim Cash and Jack Epps, Jr., to write the first draft. The research methods, by Epps, included attendance at several declassified Topgun classes at Miramar and gaining experience by being flown in an F-14. The first draft failed to impress Bruckheimer and Simpson, and is considered to be very different from the final product in numerous ways.<ref>Special Edition DVD, Interview with Jack Epps</ref> Tony Scott was hired to direct on the strength of a commercial he had done for Swedish automaker [[Saab automobile|Saab]] in the early 1980s, where a [[Saab 900]] turbo is shown racing a [[Saab 37 Viggen]] fighter jet.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jets, jeans and Hovis|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2007/aug/24/1|newspaper=The Guardian|date=12 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nActor [[Matthew Modine]] turned down the role of [[Pete Mitchell (Top Gun)|LT Pete \"Maverick\" Mitchell]] (that went to Tom Cruise) because he felt the film's pro-military stance went against his politics. The character of Chipper Piper was created just for Pasdar as Scott loved his performance.<ref>https://www.phillymag.com/news/2007/06/19/exit-interview-adrian-pasdar/%3Famp%3D1&ved=2ahUKEwiFt9y_2LPkAhWGd98KHX1fDj04ChAWMAJ6BAgIEAE&usg=AOvVaw0BwMNNZVyZdJT2v7LgFHlg</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://nymag.com/news/intelligencer/encounter/57174/|title=154 Minutes With Matthew Modine|date=June 15\u201322, 2009|last=Murphy|first=Tim|magazine=New York magazine}}</ref>\n\nThe producers wanted the assistance of the US Navy in the production of the film. The Navy was influential in relation to script approval, which resulted in changes being made. The opening dogfight was moved to international waters as opposed to [[Cuba]], the language was toned down, and a scene that involved a crash on the deck of an aircraft carrier was also scrapped.<ref>Special Edition DVD, Interview with the producers</ref> Maverick's love interest was also changed from a female enlisted member of the Navy to a civilian contractor with the Navy, due to the US military's prohibition of fraternization between officers and enlisted personnel.<ref name=\"Top Gun Movie -The 80s Rewind\" /> The \"Charlie\" character also replaced an aerobics instructor from an early draft as a love interest for Maverick after producers were introduced to [[Christine Fox|Christine \"Legs\" Fox]], a civilian mathematician employed by the [[Center for Naval Analyses]] as a specialist in Maritime Air Superiority (MAS), developing tactics for aircraft carrier defense.<ref name=Richman1985/>\n\n[[Julianne Phillips]] was in consideration for the role of Charlie, and had been scheduled to perform a screen test opposite Tom Cruise.<ref name=AFI/>\n\nRear Admiral Pete \"Viper\" Pettigrew, a former Navy aviator, Vietnam War veteran, and Topgun instructor served as a technical advisor on the film, and also made a cameo appearance in the film as a colleague of Charlie's.\n\nFormer Top Gun instructor pilot and Congressman [[Duke Cunningham|Randy \"Duke\" Cunningham]] claimed to have been the inspiration for Pete Mitchell, although the film's producers have denied that the character was based on any specific Naval Aviator.<ref>{{cite news| first=Alex| last=Roth| newspaper=The San Diego Union-Tribune| url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/politics/cunningham/20060115-9999-lz1n15legend.html| title= down Cunningham's legend| date=2006-01-15| page=A-1| accessdate=2006-02-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:VF-111 TOPGUN MOVIE.jpg|thumb|F-14A Tomcats of Fighter Squadrons [[VF-51]] \"Screaming Eagles\" and [[VF-111 (1956-95)|VF-111]] \"Sundowners\", and F-5E/F Tiger IIs of the Navy Fighter Weapons School]]\n\nThe Navy made several aircraft from F-14 fighter squadron [[VF-51]] \"Screaming Eagles\" (which Tom Skerritt mentions in the scene at his home) available for the film. Paramount paid as much as US$7,800 per hour (equivalent to ${{inflation|US|7800|1985|r=-2|fmt=c}} today) for fuel and other operating costs whenever aircraft were flown outside their normal duties. Shots of the aircraft carrier sequences were filmed aboard USS ''Enterprise'', showing aircraft from F-14 squadrons [[VF-114]] \"Aardvarks\" and [[VFA-213|VF-213]] \"Black Lions\".<ref>[http://www.topgunbio.com/ Baranek, Dave \"Bio\", \"Topgun Days\"], Skyhorse Publishing, 2010. {{ISBN|978-1-61608-005-1}}</ref> The majority of the carrier flight deck shots were of normal aircraft operations and the film crew had to take what they could get, save for the occasional flyby which the film crew would request. During filming, director Tony Scott wanted to shoot aircraft landing and taking off, back-lit by the sun. During one particular filming sequence, the ship's commanding officer changed the ship's course, thus changing the light. When Scott asked if they could continue on their previous course and speed, he was informed by the commander that it cost US$25,000 (equivalent to ${{inflation|US|25000|1985|r=-3|fmt=c}} today) to turn the ship, and to continue on course. Scott wrote the carrier's captain a US$25,000 check so that the ship could be turned and he could continue shooting for another five minutes.<ref>Special Edition DVD, Interview with Tony Scott and Pete Pettigrew</ref>\n\n[[File:Filming of Top Gun movie (01) 1985.jpg|thumb|upright=.75|Filming and [[clapperboard]] of ''Top Gun'' on July 5, 1985.]]\n\nMost of the sequences of the aircraft maneuvering over land were shot at [[Naval Air Station Fallon]], in [[Nevada]], using ground-mounted cameras. Air-to-air shots were filmed using a [[Learjet]], piloted by Astrovision inventor and legendary pilot [[Clay Lacy]]. His name is misspelled in the closing credits, as Clay Lacey. [[Grumman]], manufacturer of the F-14, was commissioned by Paramount Pictures to create camera pods to be placed upon the aircraft<ref>{{cite book |last=Rogers |first=Pauline |date=1998 |title=Contemporary Cinematographers on Their Art |url=https://archive.org/details/contemporarycine00roge |url-access=registration |publisher=CRC Press |page=[https://archive.org/details/contemporarycine00roge/page/222 222] |isbn=9781136045776 }}</ref> that could be pointed toward either the front or rear of the aircraft providing outside shots at high altitude.\n\nIn July 1985, [[Kansas City Barbeque]] served as a filming location for two scenes. The first scene features Goose and Maverick singing \"[[Great Balls of Fire]]\" while seated at the piano. The final scene, where \"[[You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin']]\" can be heard on the restaurant's jukebox, was also filmed at the restaurant. Both scenes were filmed consecutively. After release of the movie, the restaurant went on to collect a significant amount of memorabilia from the motion picture until a kitchen fire on June 26, 2008, destroyed much of the restaurant. Some memorabilia and props, including the original piano used in the film, survived the fire, and the restaurant re-opened in November 2008.\n\nRenowned aerobatic pilot [[Art Scholl]] was hired to do in-flight camera work for the film. The original script called for a [[Spin (flight)|flat spin]], which Scholl was to perform and capture on a camera on the aircraft. The aircraft was observed to spin through its recovery altitude, at which time Scholl radioed \"I have a problem... I have a real problem\". He was unable to recover from the spin and crashed his [[Pitts Special]] bi-plane into the [[Pacific Ocean]] off the Southern California coast near [[Carlsbad, California|Carlsbad]] on September 16, 1985. Neither Scholl's body nor his aircraft was recovered, leaving the official cause of the accident unknown.<ref>Ashurst, Sam (November 4, 2008). [http://www.totalfilm.com/features/hollywood-s-deadliest-stunts Hollywood's deadliest stunts]. ''[[Total Film]]''.</ref> ''Top Gun'' was dedicated to Scholl's memory.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mw95w0WFqA0&t=6m12s|title=Top Gun \u2013 Abspann (Sat 1, 1989)|date=April 23, 2008|work=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nThe film was shot in the [[Super 35]] format, as anamorphic lenses were too large to fit inside the cockpits of the fighter jets.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Burum |editor1-first=Stephen |date=2007 |title=American Cinematographer Manual, Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1cYYAQAAIAAJ&q=&#034;optics+allow+this+is+one+of+the+reasons&#034;&dq=&#034;optics+allow+this+is+one+of+the+reasons&#034;&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjf9rvMm63kAhWClp4KHZHtCwgQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg |publisher=ASC Press |page=40 |isbn=9780935578317}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n{{further|Top Gun (soundtrack)}}\nThe ''Top Gun'' soundtrack is one of the most popular soundtracks to date, reaching [[RIAA certification|9\u00d7 Platinum certification]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?artist=%22Top+Gun%22# |title=RIAA Searchable Gold and Platinum Database |accessdate=July 6, 2012}} (may have to press the Search button)</ref> and #1 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 200 albums chart for five nonconsecutive weeks in the summer and fall of 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/1986-08-02/billboard-200|title=Top 200 Albums \u2013 Billboard|work=Billboard}}</ref> [[Harold Faltermeyer]], who previously worked with both [[Jerry Bruckheimer]] and [[Don Simpson]] on ''[[Beverly Hills Cop]]'', was sent the script of ''Top Gun'' by Bruckheimer before filming began. [[Giorgio Moroder]] and [[Tom Whitlock]] worked on numerous songs including the Oscar-winning \"[[Take My Breath Away]]\". [[Kenny Loggins]] performed two songs on the soundtrack, \"[[Playing with the Boys]]\", and \"[[Danger Zone (song)|Danger Zone]]\". [[Berlin (band)|Berlin]] recorded the song \"Take My Breath Away\", which would later win numerous awards, sending the band to international acclaim. After the release of Loggins's single \"Danger Zone\", sales of the album exploded, selling 7 million in the [[United States]] alone. On the re-release of the soundtrack in 2000, two songs that had been omitted from the original album (and had been released many years before the film was made), \"[[Great Balls of Fire]]\" by [[Jerry Lee Lewis]] and \"[[You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin']]\" by [[The Righteous Brothers]], were added. The soundtrack also includes \"[[Top Gun Anthem|''Top Gun'' Anthem]]\" and \"Memories\" by [[Steve Stevens]]/Faltermeyer and Faltermeyer.\n\nOther artists were considered for the soundtrack project but did not participate. [[Bryan Adams]] was considered as a potential candidate but refused to participate because he felt the film glorified war.<ref>{{URL|http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/21800%7C0/Top-Gun.html}}</ref> The band [[Toto (band)|Toto]] was originally meant to record \"Danger Zone\", and had also written and recorded a song \"Only You\" for the soundtrack. However, there was a dispute between Toto's lawyers and the producers of the film, paving the way for Loggins to record \"Danger Zone\" and \"Only You\" being omitted from the film entirely.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toto99.com/blog2010/index.php?/archives/785-TOP-GUN-soundtrack.html|title=toto99.com \u2013 Official TOTO Website \u2013 Encyclopedia|work=toto99.com}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n===Theatrical===\nThe film's premiere was held in New York City on May 12, 1986<ref name=premiere>{{cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/actor-tom-cruise-attends-the-top-gun-premiere-party-on-may-news-photo/156180769|title=Actor Tom Cruise attends the 'Top Gun' Premiere Party on May 12, 1986|accessdate=July 21, 2019|last=Gallela|first=Ron|via=[[Getty Images]]}}</ref> with another held in San Diego on May 15.<ref name=AFI>{{AFI film|id=57496}}</ref>\n\nThe film opened in the United States in 1,028 theaters on May 16, 1986.<ref name=BOM/>\n\n=== Home media ===\nIn addition to its box office success, ''Top Gun'' went on to break further records in the then still-developing home video market. It was the first new-release blockbuster on video cassette to be priced as low as $26.95 and, backed by a massive $8 million marketing campaign, including a ''Top Gun''-themed [[Diet Pepsi]] commercial,<ref>Taylor, Rod (March 1, 2005). [http://promomagazine.com/entertainmentmarketing/marketing_high_flyer/ High Flyer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060505151117/http://promomagazine.com/entertainmentmarketing/marketing_high_flyer/ |date=2006-05-05 }}. ''Promo''.</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ri5msDcS_DI&t=30 Opening to Top Gun 1987 VHS], tape print date: February 23, 1987 (posted to YouTube on March 5, 2016)</ref> the advance demand was such that the film became the best-selling videocassette in the industry's history on pre-orders alone, with over 1.9 million units ordered before its launch on March 10, 1987.<ref name=Takeoff>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|title='Top Gun' Cassettes In Record Takeoff: 1,900,000 Units|page=1|last=Bierbaum|first=Tom|date=March 4, 1987}}</ref> It eventually sold a record 2.9 million units.<ref name=\"price\">{{cite news |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DE0D9133FF934A25756C0A96E948260 |title=Wearing Spielberg Down To Put 'E.T.' on Cassette |author=Harmetz, Aljean |date=May 17, 1988}}</ref>\n\nThe film was first released in the U.S. on DVD under Paramount Pictures on October 21, 1998 and included the film in both Widescreen (non-anamorphic [[Univisium]] 2.00:1) and Full Screen ([[open matte]]) versions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/dvd/Top-Gun-DVD/2639/|title= Top Gun DVD|website=Blu-ray.com|date=October 21, 1998|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> ''Top Gun''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s home video success was again reflected by strong DVD sales, which were furthered by a Special Collector's Edition 2-disc DVD release in December 2004 in both Widescreen (anamorphic 2.39:1) and Full Screen (open matte) versions, that include new bonus features. Special features comprise [[audio commentary]] by Bruckheimer, Tony Scott and naval experts, four [[music video]]s including the \"Top Gun Anthem\" and \"Take My Breath Away\", a six-part documentary on the making of ''Top Gun'', and vintage gallery with interviews, behind-the-scenes and survival training [[featurette]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/dvd/Top-Gun-DVD/6547/|title= Top Gun DVD Widescreen Special Collector\u2019s Edition|website=Blu-ray.com|date=December 14, 2004|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, the film was first released on [[Blu-ray]] disc on July 29, 2008 with the same supplemental features as the Collector's Edition DVD and also as a 2-disc limited edition [[3-D film|3D]] copy on February 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Top-Gun-Blu-ray/475/|title= Top Gun Blu-ray|website=Blu-ray.com|date=July 29, 2008|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Top-Gun-3D-Blu-ray/60004/|title=Top Gun Limited 3D Edition / Blu-ray 3D + Blu-ray|publisher=Blu-ray.com|date=February 19, 2013|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> The remastered Blu-ray and Digital Copy version of the film was released on May 19, 2019 on [https://www.paramountmovies.com/movies/top-gun Paramount Movies].\n''Top Gun'' is scheduled to be released in the U.S. on remastered Blu-ray and 4K [[Ultra HD]] on May 19, 2020 with two new special features titled The Legacy of ''Top Gun'' and On Your Six: Thirty years of ''Top Gun'', with the remaining bonus features being ported over.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Top-Gun-Blu-ray/266605/|title=Top Gun Blu-ray + Digital|website=Blu-ray.com|date=May 19, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=26592|title=Top Gun 4K Blu-ray|publisher=Blu-ray.com|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== IMAX 3D re-release ===\n''Top Gun'' was re-released in IMAX 3D on February 8, 2013, for six days.<ref name=\"Slash Film\">{{cite news |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/top-gun-gets-imax-3d-re-release-in-february/ |title=''Top Gun'' Gets IMAX Re-Release in February |author=Lussier, Germain |publisher=Flash Film |date=2012-12-11 |accessdate=2012-12-11}}</ref> A four-minute preview of the conversion, featuring the \"Danger Zone\" flight sequence, was screened at the 2012 [[International Broadcasting Convention]] in [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]].<ref name=\"Hollywood Reporter\">{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/top-gun-coming-theaters-3d-234032 |title=''Top Gun'' Coming to Theaters in 3D |author=Giardina, Carolyn |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=2011-09-12 |accessdate=2011-09-14}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Box office ===\nThe film quickly became a success and was the highest-grossing film of 1986. It would be six months before its theater count dropped below that of its opening week.<ref name=bomweekly /> It was number one on its first weekend with a gross of US$8,193,052,<ref name=BOM/> and went on to a total domestic gross of US$176,781,728.<ref name=BOM/> Internationally it took in an estimated US$177,030,000<ref name=BOM/> for a worldwide box office total of US$353,811,728.<ref name=BOM/> The film sold an estimated 47,650,100 tickets in North America in its initial theatrical run.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=July 13, 2016|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=topgun.htm&adjust_yr=1&p=.htm|title=Top Gun (1986)|website=Box Office Mojo}}</ref>\n\nThe film grossed an additional US$3,018,873 in its IMAX re-release in 2013 bringing its domestic gross to US$179,800,601 and its worldwide gross to US$356,830,601.<ref name=BOM/>\n\n=== Critical response ===\nUpon the film's original release, critical response was mixed. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 55% based on reviews from 55 critics, with an average rating of 5.85/10. The website's critical consensus states: \"Though it features some of the most memorable and electrifying aerial footage shot with an expert eye for action, ''Top Gun'' offers too little for non-adolescent viewers to chew on when its characters aren't in the air.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/top_gun |title=Top Gun (1986) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 50 out of 100 based on 15 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/top-gun |title=Top Gun Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade A on scale of A to F.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |work= [[CinemaScore]] |url-status=live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 2018-12-20 }}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film 2.5 out of 4 stars, saying that \"Movies like ''Top Gun'' are hard to review because the good parts are so good and the bad parts are so relentless. The dogfights are absolutely the best since [[Clint Eastwood]]'s electrifying aerial scenes in [[Firefox (film)|''Firefox'']]. But look out for the scenes where the people talk to one another.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/top-gun-1986|title=Top Gun|author=Roger Ebert|work=Roger Ebert.com|date=May 16, 1986|accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\nThe film was nominated for and won many awards, most prominently for its sound and effects. The film won the following awards:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category \n! Recipients\n|-\n| 1987\n| ASCAP Film and Television Music Awards\n| Most Performed Songs from Motion Pictures \n| Giorgio Moroder and Tom Whitlock for the song \"[[Take My Breath Away]]\".\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[Academy Award]]s\n| Best Original Song \n| Giorgio Moroder (music) and Tom Whitlock (lyrics) for \"Take My Breath Away\".\n|-\n| 1986\n| Apex Scroll Awards\n| Achievement in Sound Effects\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[Brit Awards|BRIT Awards]]\n| Best Soundtrack\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[Golden Globe Award]]s\n| Best Original Song \u2013 Motion Picture \n| Giorgio Moroder (music) and Tom Whitlock (lyrics) for the song \"Take My Breath Away\".\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[Goldene Leinwand|Golden Screen Award]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[Grammy Award]]s\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Instrumental Performance|Best Pop Instrumental Performance (Orchestra, Group or Soloist)]] \n| Harold Faltermeyer and [[Steve Stevens]] for \"[[Top Gun Anthem|''Top Gun'' Anthem]]\".\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1987\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Motion Picture Sound Editors]]\n| Golden Reel Award for Best Sound Editing\n|\n|-\n| Best Sound Editing \u2013 Sound Effects\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[People's Choice Award]]s\n| Favorite Motion Picture\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| Award of the Japanese Academy\n| Best Foreign Language Film\n|\n|}\n\nThe film was nominated for the following awards:\n\n* Academy Awards (1987)<ref name=\"Oscars1987\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1987 |title=The 59th Academy Awards (1987) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=2011-10-16|work=oscars.org}}</ref>\n** Best Sound Effects Editing \u2013 [[Cecelia Hall]] and [[George Watters II]]\n** Best Film Editing \u2013 [[Billy Weber]] and [[Chris Lebenzon]]\n** Best Sound \u2013 [[Donald O. Mitchell]], [[Kevin O'Connell (sound mixer)|Kevin O'Connell]], [[Rick Kline]] and [[William B. Kaplan]]\n** Best Original Song \u2013 Giorgio Moroder and Tom Whitlock for \"Take My Breath Away\"\n* Apex Scroll Awards (1986)\n** Actress in a Supporting Role \u2013 Meg Ryan\n** Film Editing \u2013 Billy Weber and Chris Lebenzon\n** Best Original Song \u2013 Motion Picture \u2013 Giorgio Moroder (music) and Tom Whitlock (lyrics) for the song \"Take My Breath Away\".\n** Best Picture \u2013 [[Don Simpson]], [[Jerry Bruckheimer]]\n** Achievement in Compilation Soundtrack\n** Achievement in Sound\n* Golden Globe Awards (1987)\n** Best Original Score \u2013 Motion Picture \u2013 Harold Faltermeyer\n* Award of the Japanese Academy (1988)\n** Best Foreign Language Film\n* Fennecus Awards (1986)\n** Achievement in Compilation Soundtrack\n** Best Original Song \u2013 Motion Picture \u2013 Giorgio Moroder (music) and Tom Whitlock (lyrics) for the song \"Take My Breath Away\".\n** Film Editing \u2013 Billy Weber and Chris Lebenzon\n** Achievement in Sound\n** Achievement in Sound Effects\n\nIn 2008, the film was ranked at number 455 in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s list of the 500 greatest films of all time.<ref>[https://www.empireonline.com/500/8.asp The 500 Greatest Movies of All Time]. ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''.</ref> [[Yahoo! Movies]] ranked ''Top Gun'' #19 on their list of greatest action films of all-time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/|title=Yahoo Movies|work=yahoo.com}}</ref> The film was nominated multiple times for various AFI lists, but broke through only once. In 2005, the line \"I feel the need... the need for speed!\" was ranked 94 on [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes]] list.\n\n;[[American Film Institute]] list\n*[[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes]]:\n**\"I feel the need \u2014 the need for speed.\" \u2013 #94\n\n=== Effect on military recruiting ===\nMovie producer [[John Davis (producer)|John Davis]] said that ''Top Gun'' was a recruiting video for the Navy, that people saw the movie and said, \"Wow! I want to be a pilot.\" The Navy had recruitment booths in some theaters to attract enthusiastic patrons.<ref>[http://film.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/Guardian/0,4029,543821,00.html Top Gun versus Sergeant Bilko? No contest, says the Pentagon]. ''[[The Guardian]]''. August 29, 2001.</ref> After the film's release, the US Navy stated that the number of young men who joined wanting to be Naval Aviators went up by 500 percent.<ref>{{cite book|last=Robb|first=David|title=Operation Hollywood: How the Pentagon Shapes and Censors the Movies|publisher=Prometheus Books|location=New York|year=2004|pages=[https://archive.org/details/operationhollywo00robb/page/180 180\u2013182]|isbn=1-59102-182-0|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/operationhollywo00robb/page/180}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign affairs===\nOn January 23, 2011, China's state broadcaster ''[[China Central Television]]'' published a TV news story about the alleged efficiency of Chinese fighter pilots which incorporated footage from the ''Top Gun'' action sequences. Chinese internet users noticed the plagiarism, whereupon the broadcast was immediately withdrawn. Ironically, this occurred shortly after the initiation of a Chinese campaign to purge such forged reports; CCTV has declined comments on this incident.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://blogs.wsj.com/chinarealtime/2011/01/28/video-cctv-tries-to-pass-off-%E2%80%98top-gun%E2%80%99-clip-as-military-drill/ |title = Video: CCTV Tries to Pass Off \u2018Top Gun\u2019 Clip as Military Drill? |newspaper = [[The Wall Street Journal]] |last = Chin |first = Josh |date = January 28, 2011|accessdate=2018-08-20}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n{{in popular culture|section|date=July 2019}} \n[[Bomber jacket]] sales increased and [[Ray-Ban Aviator]] [[sunglasses]] jumped 40%, due to their use by characters in the film.<ref name=\"rayban\">{{cite news | work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | title=Through A Glass Darkly | url=http://www.time.com/time/archive/preview/0,10987,991503,00.html |author1=August, Melissa |author2=Derrow, Michelle |author3=Durham, Aisha |author4=Levy, Daniel S. |author5=Lofaro, Lina |author6=Spitz, David |author7=Taylor, Chris | date=July 12, 1999 |accessdate=November 8, 2006}}</ref>\n\nSince its initial release, the film has made many top film lists and has been the subject of comedic interpretation.\n\nThe 1991 film ''[[Hot Shots!]]'' was a comedy spoof of ''Top Gun''.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1991/07/31/movies/review-film-pilots-in-hot-shots-shoot-down-top-gun-in-a-hail-of-parody.html Review/Film; Pilots in 'Hot Shots!' Shoot Down 'Top Gun' In a Hail of Parody-NY Times]</ref>\n\nThe masculine theme of the film has been the subject of humorous examination, with the [[Homoeroticism|homoerotic]] subtext examined in a monologue performed by [[Quentin Tarantino]] in the 1994 film ''[[Sleep with Me]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Modleski|first1=Tania|author-link=Tania Modleski|title=Misogynist Films: Teaching Top Gun|journal=Cinema Journal|date=November 19, 2007|volume=47|issue=1|pages=102\u2013103|doi=10.1353/cj.2007.0056|issn=1527-2087}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=simmons/030904|title=ESPN.com: Page 2 : 'Talk to me, Goose. Talk to me.'|work=go.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://reelchange.net/2013/02/12/why-the-homoeroticism-in-top-gun-matters/|title=Why the Homoeroticism in \"Top Gun\" Matters|work=Reel Change|date=2013-02-12}}</ref><ref>http://www.cracked.com/funny-1906-quentin-tarantino-movies/ ''Cracked Magazine.com''\n\"Tarantino on Pop Culture (AKA If Cracked.com Was Written on Cocaine)\"</ref>\n\n''Top Gun'' is one of many war and action films, especially those by Jerry Bruckheimer, parodied in the 2004 comedy ''[[Team America: World Police]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2004/10/strings_attached.html|title=Strings Attached|journal=Slate|first=David|last=Edelstein|date=October 14, 2004}}</ref>\n\n''Top Gun'' along with ''[[A Few Good Men]]'' are recognized for being an inspiration for the TV series ''[[JAG (TV series)|JAG]]'' and for the [[NCIS (franchise)|''NCIS'' franchise]] in turn.  The entire JAG/NCIS franchise is also owned by Paramount.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Karlen|first1=Neal|title=COVER STORY;From the Man Behind 'Magnum, P.I.,' 'Top Gun' Meets 'A Few Good Men' By NEAL KARLEN|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/05/tv/cover-story-from-the-man-behind-magnum-pi-top-gun-meets-a-few-good-men.html|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=May 3, 2018|date=1995-11-05}}</ref>\n\nThe [[DisneyToon Studios]] film ''[[Planes (film)|Planes]]'' (2013), pays homage to ''Top Gun'' with Val Kilmer and Anthony Edwards appearing in the film as part of the voice cast.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywood.com/movies/disney-planes-top-gun-val-kilmer-anthony-edwards-57157487/ |title=Disney's 'Planes' Taps Val Kilmer and Anthony Edwards for 'Top Gun' Homage - PIC |last=Blauvelt  |first=Christian |date=2013-03-27 |website=hollywood.com |access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref>\n\nTwo Chinese films, 2011's ''Jian Shi Chu Ji'' (\"Skyfighters\") and 2017's ''Kong Tian Lie'' (\"[[Sky Hunter]]\"), were based on ''Top Gun''.<ref>{{cite news|author=Groffman, Nicolas|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2170552/top-gun-was-twice-remade-chinese-why-didnt-anybody-notice-clue|title=Top Gun was twice remade in Chinese, why didn't anybody notice? Clue: PLA|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=2018-10-29|accessdate=2018-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== Sequel ==\n{{main|Top Gun: Maverick}}\nA sequel has been in active development since at least 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2010/10/top_gun_2.html|title=''Top Gun 2'' is Heading to the Runway|last=Brodesser-Akner|first=Claude|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] magazine|date=October 13, 2010|accessdate=October 15, 2010}}</ref>  However plans were complicated by Scott's death in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/blogs/movie-talk/top-gun-producer-jerry-bruckheimer-reveals-won-over-233712961.html|title='Top Gun' producer Jerry Bruckheimer reveals how he won over Tom Cruise|work=Yahoo!|date=January 23, 2013|accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref> In 2013 Bruckheimer said, \"For 30 years we've been trying to make a sequel and we're not going to stop. We still want to do it with Tom and Paramount are still interested in making it. What Tom tells me is that no matter where he goes in the world, people refer to him as Maverick. It's something he is excited about so as long as he keeps his enthusiasm hopefully we'll get it made.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flickeringmyth.com/2013/06/jerry-bruckheimer-says-top-gun-2-is.html|title=Jerry Bruckheimer says Top Gun 2 is still on the cards|work=Flickering Myth|date=June 10, 2013|accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBy September 2014 it was revealed that Justin Marks was in negotiations to write the screenplay,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/top-gun-2-lands-jungle-731131|title='Top Gun 2' Lands 'Jungle Book' Writer (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 8, 2014|accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref> which was confirmed that following June.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/top-gun-2-maverick-drone-warfare-1201529697/| title='Top Gun 2\u2032 to Feature Maverick, Drone Warfare|last=Zumberge|first=Marianne|magazine=Variety|date=June 26, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015}}</ref> Marks would go on later to say that the film was a dream project for him, calling the original an \"iconic film in my memory\" due in part to it being one of the first films he remembers seeing in a movie theater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://creativescreenwriting.com/king-of-the-swingers-justin-marks-on-the-jungle-book/|title=King of the Swingers: Justin Marks on 'The Jungle Book'|first=Christopher|last=McKittrick|work=Creative Screenwriting|date=April 19, 2016|accessdate=September 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, during the promotional tour for ''[[The Mummy (2017 film)|The Mummy]]'', Cruise confirmed that a sequel to ''Top Gun'' will start filming in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/05/23/tom-cruise-top-gun-2-definitely-happening/|title=Tom Cruise Says 'Top Gun 2' Is 'Definitely Happening'|date=May 23, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> By June of the same year, he said that the title will be ''Top Gun: Maverick'' with Faltermeyer back as composer for the sequel. Cruise further stated that, \"Aviators are back, the need for speed. We're going to have big, fast machines. It's going to be a competition film, like the first one\u2026but a progression for Maverick.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/06/02/top-gun-2-title-tom-cruise-top-gun-maverick|title=In Which Tom Cruise Reveals The Title Of The TOP GUN Sequel|first=Scott|last=Wampler|date=June 2, 2017|website=Birth.Movies.Death.}}</ref> Later that month it was announced [[Joseph Kosinski]], who directed Cruise in 2013's ''[[Oblivion (2013 film)|Oblivion]]'', was set to direct the sequel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/top-gun-sequel-release-july-12-2019-tom-cruiise-joseph-kosinski-jerry-bruckheimer-paramount-1202123050/|title=Paramount Sets \u2018Top Gun 2\u2019 For July 2019; Joseph Kosinski Firmed For Tom Cruise Pic|work=Deadline Hollywood |date=June 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe release date has since been pushed back one year to June 2020, and later to December of that same year. A trailer was released for the first time at ComicCon International on July 18, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/news/ni62189853|title=\u2018Top Gun\u2019 Sequel Release Pushed Back One Year at Paramount|website=IMDb|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i6tDB7k9Ask</ref>\n\n== Video games ==\n{{Main|List of Top Gun video games}}\n''Top Gun'' also spawned a number of [[video game]]s for various platforms. The [[Top Gun (1986 video game)|original game]] was released in 1986 under the same title as the film. It was released on [[Commodore 64]], [[ZX Spectrum]], [[Amstrad CPC]], and [[Atari ST]]. Another game, also titled ''[[Top Gun (1987 video game)|Top Gun]]'', was released in 1987 for [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] (NES) and [[Nintendo VS. System]] arcade cabinets. In the 1987 game, the player pilots an F-14 Tomcat fighter, and has to complete four missions. A sequel, ''Top Gun: The Second Mission'', was released for the NES three years later.\n\nAnother game, ''[[Top Gun: Fire at Will]]'', was released in 1996 for the PC and later for the [[PlayStation|Sony PlayStation]] platform. ''[[Top Gun: Hornet's Nest]]'' was released in 1998. ''[[Top Gun: Combat Zones]]'' was released for [[PlayStation 2]] in 2001 and was subsequently released for the [[GameCube]] and [[Microsoft Windows]]. ''Combat Zones'' features other aircraft besides the F-14. In 2006, another game simply titled ''Top Gun'' was released for the [[Nintendo DS]]. A 2010 game, also titled ''[[Top Gun (2010 video game)|Top Gun]]'', retells the film's story. At E3 2011, a new game was announced, ''Top Gun: Hard Lock'', which was released in March 2012 for [[Xbox 360]], PC, and [[PlayStation 3]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Top Gun (film, 1986)}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{AFI film|id=57496}}\n* {{IMDb title|0092099}}\n* {{tcmdb title|16475}}\n* [http://www.fandango.com/movie-news/top-gun-30th-anniversary-remember-the-movie-with-this-exclusive-artwork-750546 'Top Gun' 30th Anniversary Exclusive Art Work] on [[Fandango (ticket service)|Fandango]]\n* {{Allmovie title|50435}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|top_gun}}\n* [https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=topgun.htm Top Gun] at [[Box Office Mojo]]\n* [https://www.paramountmovies.com/movies/top-gun Paramount Movies]\n{{Tony Scott}}\n{{Jerry Bruckheimer}}\n\n[[Category:1986 films]]\n[[Category:1980s action drama films]]\n[[Category:2013 3D films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American aviation films]]\n[[Category:American action drama films]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Original Song Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Cold War aviation films]]\n[[Category:Films about aviators]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on newspaper and magazine articles]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Don Simpson]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Tony Scott]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Jerry Bruckheimer]]\n[[Category:Films set in San Diego]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Films shot in San Diego]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films about the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:United States National Film Registry films]]\n[[Category:Top Gun]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Harold Faltermeyer]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Giorgio Moroder]]\n[[Category:3D re-releases]]\n", "name_user": "Mandingo30", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Top_Gun"}
